# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: french-ship-gloire
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The **armored cruiser** was a type of warship of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] It was designed like other types of cruisers to operate as a long-range, independent warship, capable of defeating any ship apart from a pre-dreadnought battleship and fast enough to outrun any battleship it encountered.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] For many decades, naval technology had not advanced far enough for designers to produce a cruiser that combined an armored belt with the long-range and high speed required to fulfill its mission.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] For this reason, beginning in the 1880s and 1890s, many navies preferred to build protected cruisers, which only relied on a lightly armored deck to protect the vital parts of the ship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, by the late 1880s, the development of modern rapid-fire breech-loading cannons and high-explosive shells made the reintroduction of side armor a necessity.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The invention of case-hardened armor in the mid-1890s offered effective protection with less weight than previously.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Varying in size, the armored cruiser was distinguished from other types of cruiser by its belt armor—thick iron (or later steel) plating on much of the hull to protect the ship from shellfire much like that on battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The first armored cruiser, the Imperial Russian Navy's *General-Admiral*, was launched in 1873 and combined sail and steam propulsion.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] By the 1890s, cruisers had abandoned sail and took on a modern appearance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] In 1908, the armored cruiser was supplanted by the battlecruiser, which, with armament equivalent to that of a dreadnought battleship and speed equivalent to that of a cruiser, was faster and more powerful than an armored cruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] At around the same time there was a successor to the protected cruiser, the "light cruiser" which described small cruisers with armored belts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Although they were now considered second-rate ships, armored cruisers were still widely used in World War I due to their speed and range, and being able to outgun all but battlecruisers and battleships (both pre-dreadnought and dreadnought types).
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] A handful survived in one form or another until World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Only one, the Greek Navy's *Georgios Averof*, has survived to the modern day as a museum ship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruiser was developed in the 1870s as an attempt to combine the virtues of the armored ironclad warship and the fast and long-ranged, but unarmored, cruisers of the time.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Such a ship was desirable to protect overseas trade and, especially for the French and British, to police their vast overseas empires.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The concern within higher naval circles was that without ships that could fulfill these requirements and incorporate new technology, their fleet would become obsolete and ineffective should a war at sea arise.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Concern over obsolescence in official circles was further fueled by the race between the increasing size of naval guns and of armor strong enough to withstand such fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] In 1860, one of the largest naval cannons in standard use had a bore of 8 inches (203 mm) and fired a 68-pound (31 kg) solid shot or approximately 51-pound (23 kg) spherical shell.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] By 1884, guns with as wide a bore as 16.25 inches (413 mm), firing an 1,800-pound (816 kg) exploding shell, were being mounted on naval vessels.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] This gun could penetrate up to 34 inches of wrought iron, the earliest form of naval armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] These were muzzle-loading guns, as had been used on ships from the 1500s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Breech-loading cannon, which were readopted into naval use in the 1870s, were more destructive than muzzle loaders due to their higher rate of fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The development of rifled cannon, which improved accuracy, and advancements in shells were other factors.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Although a cruiser would not likely face the largest-caliber guns of a battleship and many navies commonly used smaller weapons as they did not wear out as fast as larger ones did, cruisers still needed some form of protection to preclude being shot to pieces.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The adoption of rolled iron armor in 1865 and sandwich armor in 1870 gave ships a chance to withstand fire from larger guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Both these protective schemes used wood as an important component, which made them extremely heavy and limited speed, the key factor in a cruiser's ability to perform its duties satisfactorily.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Powered by both sail and steam but without the additional weight of armor, these ships could reach speeds of up to 16 or 17 knots.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The most powerful among them were the British *Inconstant*, the U.S.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Navy's *Wampanoag* and the French *Duquesne*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The British especially had hoped to rely on these vessels to serve the more distant reaches of its empire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] In the aftermath of the Battle of Hampton Roads in 1862, where United States wooden warships were defeated by the Confederate ironclad CSS *Virginia*, the Admiralty realized that its ships could theoretically encounter an ironclad in any theater of operation.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Ship propulsion was improving but was also taking time to develop.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Naval engines in the 1860s were single-expansion types, in which steam was expanded into a cylinder, pushed a piston and was released.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Compounding, where steam is passed through a series of cylinders of increasing size before being released, was a more efficient process; it allowed the steam to generate more energy and use less coal to go the same distance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] With greater efficiency came increasingly complex machinery and the larger potential for breakdown.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, advances in metallurgy and engineering, the potential for smaller bunkerage and the successful use of compounding in commercial engines made it an attractive option for naval engines, as well.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] By the 1870s, compound engines had become standard for warships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Compounding by itself did not increase power or speed significantly, although it allowed for a much greater operating range.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Forced-draught systems would help increase power and speed but would not come into use until the early 1890s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Russian navy became the first to produce an armored warship intended for commerce raiding, with *General-Admiral*, begun in 1870 and launched in 1873, often referred to as the first armored cruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Armed with six 8-inch (203 mm) and two 6-inch (152 mm) guns, she and her sister *Gerzog Edinburgski* were not fully armored but protected only by a narrow belt along the waterline.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] This belt, moreover, was so heavy that it sat below the ships' waterlines, which limited its benefit still further.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Since they were iron-hulled, however, they were more durable than their wooden counterparts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] With a top speed of only 12.3 knots (22.8 km/h) and a high coal consumption, which necessitated a full sailing rig, they were not really suited for the role of cruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Nevertheless, these ships were considered a new threat to British commerce in the event of war, the rationale being that any vessel, regardless of its speed, could technically be a threat to overseas commerce.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The British responded with *Shannon*, begun in 1873, launched in 1875 and armed with two 10-inch (254 mm) and seven 9-inch (229 mm) rifled guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Two ships of the *Nelson* class followed, armed with four 10-inch and eight 9-inch guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] These early armored cruisers were essentially scaled-down versions of the first-rate ironclad warships of the time and, like their Russian counterparts, were essentially belted cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Their 9-inch belts were thicker than that of the Russians but did not extend the full length of the hull due to weight but tapered off at both ends.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Past this belt, the designers placed a 3-inch (76 mm) armored deck, situated deepest in the ships, to guard magazines and machinery against plunging fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Above this deck, space was allocated for coal bunkers and storerooms.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The bunkers served as added protection, since two feet of coal was considered the equivalent of one foot of steel.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Also, if either of the ships became flooded from battle damage, it was hoped the contents of the bunkers and storerooms would aid in their continued buoyancy.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Because of this unarmored protection, these ships could be considered the first protected cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, these ships also shared the liabilities of the Russian ones and because of this, the British Navy was never happy with them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Shannon*'s top speed of 12.25 knots (22.69 km/h) and *Nelson*'s of 14 knots (26 km/h) made them too slow to deal with fast cruisers and they were not armored well enough to take on a first-class battleship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Their armor belts also sat below the ships' waterlines, which made them of limited benefit.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The underlying problem with these early warships was that technology had not caught up to the demands being made of them; therefore, they represented a series of compromises and could not be fully effective.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They were typically powered by double-expansion steam engines fed by boilers which generated steam at perhaps 60 or 70 psi pressure, which gave relatively poor efficiency and short range.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Even with improved engines, the dearth of overseas refueling stations made a full sailing rig a necessity.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] (The loss of HMS *Captain* in 1870 with nearly all of her 500-man crew illustrated graphically what could happen in a heavy sea with a steam-and-sail turret ship.) Consequently, armored cruisers retained a more traditional broadside arrangement.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Their armor was distributed in a thick belt around the waterline along most of their length; the gun positions on deck were not necessarily armored at all.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The limitations of these ships would not be rectified fully until decades after their construction.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Meanwhile, a battle in May 1877 between the British unarmored cruiser *Shah* and the Peruvian monitor *Huáscar* demonstrated the need for more and better-protected cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Shah* and the smaller wooden corvette *Amethyst* hit *Huáscar* more than 50 times without causing significant damage.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Peruvian ship had an inexperienced crew unused to its cumbersome machinery, and managed to fire only six rounds, all of which missed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The engagement demonstrated the value of cruisers with armor protection.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] During the 1870s, the rapid increase in the size and power of armor-piercing guns caused problems for the designers of battleships and cruisers alike.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Even a ship designed with adequate armor protection from the current generation of guns might be vulnerable to new guns powerful enough to penetrate its armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Consequently, naval designers tried a novel method of armoring their ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The vital parts—engines, boilers, magazines and enough hull structure to keep the ship stable in the event of damage—could be positioned underneath an armored deck just below the waterline.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] This deck, which would only be struck very obliquely by shells, could be thinner and lighter than belt armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The sides of the ship would be entirely unarmored but would be as effective as an armored belt which would not stop shellfire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Cruisers designed along these guidelines, known as protected cruisers, superseded armored cruisers in the 1880s and early 1890s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] As mentioned earlier, the armored cruiser *Shannon* was the first ship to make use of an armored deck.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, by the end of the 1870s, ships could be found with full–length armored decks and little or no side armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Italian *Italia* class of very fast battleships had armored decks and guns but no side armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The British used a full-length armored deck in their *Comus* class of corvettes started in 1878; however the *Comus* class were designed for colonial service and were only capable of 13 knots (24 km/h) speed, not fast enough for commerce protection or fleet duties.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The breakthrough for the protected cruiser design came with the Chilean *Esmeralda*, designed and built by the British firm Armstrong at their Elswick yard.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Esmeralda*, with a high speed of 18 knots (33 km/h), dispensed entirely with sails and carried an armament of two 10-inch and six 6-inch guns, considered very powerful for a ship her size.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Her protection scheme, inspired by the *Italia* class, included a full–length protected deck up to 2 inches (51 mm) thick, and a cork-filled cofferdam along her sides.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Esmeralda* set the tone for cruiser construction for the years to come, with "Elswick cruisers" on a similar design being constructed for Italy, China, Japan, Argentina, Austria and the United States.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Protected cruisers became attractive for two reasons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] First, the concept of the armored cruiser was not embraced wholeheartedly in naval circles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Second, several navies were caught in a race between armor thickness and the size of main guns and did not have the money to spend on battleships and armored cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The use of smaller, cheaper cruisers was a better alternative.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The French navy adopted the protected cruiser wholeheartedly in the 1880s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The *Jeune Ecole* school of thought, which proposed a navy composed of fast cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo-boats for coast defense, was particularly influential in France.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The first French protected cruiser was *Sfax*, laid down in 1882, and followed by six classes of protected cruiser – and no armored cruisers until *Dupuy de Lôme*, laid down in 1888 but not finished until 1895.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Dupuy de Lôme* was a revolutionary ship, being the first French armored cruiser to dispose entirely of masts, and sheathed in steel armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, she and two others were not sufficiently seaworthy, and their armor could be penetrated by modern quick-firing guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Thus from 1891 to 1897 the French reverted to the construction of protected cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The British Royal Navy was equivocal about which protection scheme to use until 1887.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The large *Imperieuse* class, begun in 1881 and finished in 1886, were built as armored cruisers but were often referred to as protected cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] While they carried an armored belt some 10 in thick, the belt only covered 140 ft (43 m) of the 315 ft (96 m) length of the ship, and was submerged below the waterline at full load.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The real protection of the class came from the armored deck 4 in (102 mm) thick, and the arrangement of coal bunkers to prevent flooding.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] These ships were also the last armored cruisers to be designed with sails.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, on trials it became clear that the masts and sails did more harm than good; they were removed and replaced by a single military mast with machine guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The next class of small cruisers in the Royal Navy, the *Mersey* class, were protected cruisers, but the Royal Navy then returned to the armored cruiser with the *Orlando* class, begun in 1885 and completed in 1889.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The navy judged the *Orlando*s inferior to protected cruisers and built exclusively protected cruisers immediately afterwards, including some very large, fast ships like the 14,000-ton *Powerful* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, the *Orlando*s were the first class of cruiser to use the triple-expansion engine.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Because this type of reciprocating engine used the steam in three stages, it was more fuel-efficient than earlier compound engines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] It also used steam of higher pressure, 60 poundforce per square inch, as compared to the 25 to 30 poundforce in earlier engines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] With these engineering developments, warships could now dispense with sails and be entirely steam-driven.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The only major naval power to retain a preference for armored cruisers during the 1880s was Russia.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Russian Navy laid down four armored cruisers and one protected cruiser during the decade, all being large ships with sails.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The development of rapid–fire cannons in the late 1880s forced a change in cruiser design.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Since a large number of hits at or near the waterline could negate the effect of water–excluding material used in protected cruisers, side armor again became a priority.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, it had to cover not just guns and the waterline but also much of the hull structure in–between; otherwise, the equally new high–explosive shells could penetrate and destroy much of the unarmored portion of the ship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Another development was the publication in 1890 of American naval strategist Alfred Thayer Mahan's book *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruisers built in the mid– to late–1890s were often as large and expensive as pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They combined long range, high speed and an armament approaching that of battleship with enough armor to protect them against quick-firing guns, considered the most important weapons afloat at the time.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Their speed was made possible due to another development, case-hardened steel armor—first Harvey armor and then crucially Krupp armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The higher tensile strength of these armors compared to nickel steel and mild steel made it feasible to put a light yet useful armor belt on a large cruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They saved further weight by not requiring a heavy timber backing, as previous armor plating had, to soften and spread the force of the impact from oncoming shells; 2.5 inches (64 mm) of teak to give a fair surface upon which to attach them was all that was needed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Moreover, this belt could also be much wider than previously, covering the center of the hull, where the ammunition and engines were located, from the main deck to five feet below the waterline.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Steel bulkheads added strength to the hull, while armor as thick as the belt covered the guns and heavier protection surrounded the conning tower.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] With these improvements, the ships became more fully protected than was possible previously.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They were also expensive to maintain at fighting strength as they required a greater number of stokers to feed the boilers than a battleship when steaming at flank speed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The ideas presented by Mahan prompted French Admiral Ernest François Fournier to write his book *La flotte necessaire* in 1896.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Fournier argued that a fleet of technologically advanced armored cruisers and torpedo craft would be powerful and flexible enough to engage in a wide range of activity and overwhelm potential enemies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] French naval and government circles embraced this ideal mutually and even advocates of battleships over cruisers admitted the latter's potential usefulness in scouting and commercial warfare.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The result was the building of increasingly large armored cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Jeanne d'Arc*, laid down in 1896, displaced 11,000 tons, carried a mixed armament of 194-millimetre (7.6 in) and 138-millimetre (5.4 in) guns, and had a 150-millimetre (5.9 in) belt of Harvey armor over her machinery spaces.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The 12,300-ton *Léon Gambetta* class and 14,000-ton *Edgar Quinet* class followed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The *Edgar Quinet*s, slightly faster at 23 knots, were armed with 14 194-millimetre (7.6 in) guns and carried up to 170-millimetre (6.7 in) of armor on their belts, almost 100-millimetre (3.9 in) on their decks and 150-millimetre (5.9 in) on their turrets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] At 21 knots, the *Cressy*s were slower than the newer French cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, their 6-inch (152 mm) belt of Krupp steel was expected to keep out armor-piercing shells from a 6-inch (152 mm) quick-firing gun at likely battle ranges, while their two 9.2-inch (233.7 mm) and 12 6-inch (152 mm) guns offered comparable firepower.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The 2,500-ton weight of their belt armor was an improvement over the 1809 tons of the otherwise similar *Diadem* class and very similar to that of the *Canopus* class of battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The *Cressy*s were the beginning of a rapid expansion in British cruiser construction.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Between 1899 and 1905, seven classes of armored cruisers were either completed or laid down, a total of 35 ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Japan, which now received British technical assistance in naval matters and purchased larger vessels from France and Britain, began an armored cruiser program of its own.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The core of this 109-ship build-up was the "Six-Six Program" of six battleships and six (eventually eight) armored cruisers comparable to the British *Cressy* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They were considered a compromise between cruiser and battleship and were intended to augment capital ship strength in battle squadrons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] This practice would persist until World War I.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The first United States armored cruiser, USS *Maine*, was launched in 1889 but not completed until 1895 due to a three-year delay in the delivery of her armor plate.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] However, *Maine* was laid down before Harvey or Krupp armor was available and could not benefit from the advantage in weight these much lighter armors offered.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] She was redesignated a "second-class battleship" in 1894, an awkward compromise reflecting that, at 16.45 knots, she was considerably slower than other cruisers and weaker than first-line battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Her destruction in Havana harbor in 1898 was a catalyst in starting the Spanish–American War.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Shortly after the war ended, the Navy laid down six *Pennsylvania*-class armored cruisers to take advantage of lessons learned and better control the large sea areas the nation had just gained.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Much larger than their predecessors (displacing 14,500 tons as compared to 8150 for *New York*), the *Pennsylvania*s "were closer to light battleships than to cruisers," according to naval historian William Friedman.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They carried four 8-inch (203 mm) and 14 6-inch (152 mm) guns, 6 inches (152 mm) of armor on their belts, 6.5 inches (165 mm) on their turrets and 9 inches (229 mm) on their conning towers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Their deck armor was light at 1.5 inches (38 mm) for flat surfaces and 3 inches (76 mm) for sloped, a compromise made for faster speed (22 knots, compared with 20 knots for *Brooklyn*).
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Improved ammunition made their main guns as powerful as the 12-inch (305 mm) guns of the battleship *Iowa* and their use of state instead of city names, usually reserved for capital ships, emphasized their kinship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] More often, they were seen fighting in a battle line.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They would not been seen in their designed role until World War I.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Even with all their improvements and apparent performance, opinion on the armored cruiser was mixed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Navy in hearings before the House of Representatives gave testimony to the effect that no armored cruisers were further planned nor to it knowledge were armored cruisers being built by any major naval power worldwide.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Armored cruisers were used with success in the line of battle by the Japanese at the Battle of Tsushima in 1905.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Of the battle damage received by the Japanese, the armored cruiser *Nisshin* received eight hits, which destroyed three of her 8-inch (203 mm) guns, killed five crew members and injured 90 more (one of the wounded being Isoroku Yamamoto, who would later plan the attack on Pearl Harbor).
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] None of the other Japanese armored cruisers suffered serious damage or large loss of life.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Iwate* was hit 16 times but no one onboard was killed and only 15 were wounded.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Except for *Kasagi*, all the cruisers present at Tsushima that morning were still battle-ready in the evening.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Danish Navy Commander William Hovgaard, who would later become president of New York Shipbuilding and serve on the U.S.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Buoyed with their success at Tsushima, Japan laid down the four *Tsukuba*-class cruisers between 1905 and 1908.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] At a speed of 20.5 knots, they carried an extremely heavy main armament of four 12-inch (305 mm) guns, 8 inches (203 mm) of belt and turret armor and 3 inches (76 mm) of deck armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The *Tsukuba*s were intended to take the place of aging battleships and thus showed Japan's intention of continuing to use armored cruisers in fleet engagements.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Navy raised the main gun caliber of its cruisers with its *Tennessee* class, laid down between 1902 and 1904.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] These mounted four 10-inch (254 mm) and 16 6-inch (152 mm) guns, the former a size previously allocated to battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] While they had thinner armor than the *Pennsylvania*s (5 inches (127 mm) on their belts and 1 inch (25 mm) on their decks) due to newly imposed congressional restraints on tonnage, they could still steam at 22 knots.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They were built as a fast, powerful response in the eventuality of a Pacific war and were the largest and last American armored cruisers built.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The British also considered 10-inch (254 mm) and 12-inch (305 mm) guns for its *Minotaur*-class cruisers, the culmination of its armored cruiser building program.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They displaced 14,600 tons, were capable of 23 knots and were armed with four 9.2-inch (234 mm) and 10 7.5-inch (191 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] By the time these ships were commissioned, Britain possessed the largest armored cruiser force in the world.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Undaunted and fully engaged in a naval arms race with the British, the Germans also continued to build armored cruisers, partly from their faith in them as fighting units and commerce raiders, partly from Japan's success.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Between 1897 and 1906 they laid down eight of them for use on overseas stations.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The initial two, SMS *Fürst Bismarck* and SMS *Prinz Heinrich*, were armed with 9.44-inch (240 mm) guns; the six that followed had 8.2-inch (208 mm) guns of a more modern design.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The final pair, *Scharnhorst* and *Gneisenau*, displaced 12,781 tons, steamed at 23.5 knots, carried 6 inches (152 mm) of belt and 2 inches (51 mm) of deck armor and were armed with eight 8.2-inch (208 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Another powerful armored cruiser was the Russian *Rurik*, completed in 1908.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Armed with four 10-inch (254 mm) in two twin turrets fore and aft and eight 8-inch (203 mm) in turrets along the ship's sides, she displaced 15,190 tons and carried a 6-inch (152 mm) belt, two armored decks and 8-inch (203 mm) armor on her turrets and conning tower.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] *Rurik* was unusual in that she was Russian designed but British built; the Russian Navy was not usually a customer of British shipyards.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] She was reportedly one of the best armored cruisers built, with an advanced sprinkler protection for the magazines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Intended as the first of a three-ship class, *Rurik*'s sisters were cancelled with the advent of the battlecruiser HMS *Invincible*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] "The supreme embodiment of the armored cruiser," in historian Robert K.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Massie's words, was the German ship SMS *Blücher*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] An enlarged version of the *Scharnhorst* class with a speed of 24.25 knots, armed with 12 8.2-inch (208 mm) and eight 5.9-inch (150 mm) guns, *Blücher* was planned as an armored cruiser in part because the British had misled the Germans on the *Invincible*s then being constructed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Germans expected these new British ships to be armed with six or eight 9.2 in (23 cm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] One week after the final decision to construct *Blücher*, the German naval attache learned they would carry eight 30.5 cm (12.0 in) guns, the same type mounted on battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] With no funds available to redesign *Blücher*, work was ordered to proceed as scheduled.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Although much more powerful than a typical armored cruiser, she was significantly weaker than the new British battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] By the time these new armored cruisers were entering service, such types of ships had reached the end of its development.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Thirty percent was the ratio by which frigates had been faster than ships of the line in the days of sail.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] If a battleship sailed at 20 knots, this would mean that an armored cruiser would have to steam at least 26 or 27 knots.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] To fulfill these criteria, however, armored cruisers would have to be built much larger and take on a different form than they had in the past.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] First Sea Lord "Jacky" Fisher, an advocate of armored cruisers as more useful than battleships to safeguard British trade and territorial interests, saw his efforts justified; his belief that "speed is armor" would lead him to create the battlecruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The battlecruiser HMS *Invincible* and her two sister ships were designed specifically to fulfill these requirements.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Because they carried the heavy guns normally ascribed to battleships, they could also theoretically hold their place in a battle line more readily than armored cruisers and serve as the "battleship-cruiser" for which Hovgaard had argued after Tsushima.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] All these factors made battlecruisers attractive fighting units, although Britain, Germany and Japan would be the only powers to build them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] They also meant that the armored cruiser as it had been known was now outmoded and no more were built after 1910.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Later in the same address is this: "Every argument used against [armored cruisers] holds true for battle-cruisers of the *Invincible* type, except that the latter, if wounded, would be fit to lie in the line, owing to her great armament.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Although pre-dreadnought battleships and armored cruisers were outclassed by modern battleship and battlecruiser designs, respectively, armored cruisers still played an active role in World War I.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Their armor and firepower was sufficient to defeat other cruiser types and armed merchant vessels, while their speed and range made them particularly useful for extended operations out in the high seas.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Some German and Royal Navy vessels, like HMS *Good Hope*, were allocated to remote naval squadrons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Many other vessels however, were formed into independent squadrons for patrolling European waters and accompanied capital ships every time the latter made forays out of port.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] At the Battle of Coronel, the German armored cruisers SMS *Scharnhorst* and SMS *Gneisenau* scored a resounding victory over British naval forces from the West Indies Station.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] With newer ships, superior gunnery and optimal logistics, the Germans sank the Royal Navy armored cruisers HMS *Monmouth* and HMS *Good Hope*, with the loss of over 1,500 British sailors and officers (including Rear-Admiral Christopher Cradock).
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] This was one of the last battles involving armored cruisers as the chief adversaries; all subsequent engagements were dominated by battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Moreover, the timing could not have been worse for British morale.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Six weeks earlier, the armored cruisers HMS *Cressy*, HMS *Hogue* and HMS *Aboukir* had all been sunk on the same day by the German submarine U-9.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Five weeks later, the Battle of the Falkland Islands showed graphically how much technology and tactics had changed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] SMS *Scharnhorst* and SMS *Gneisenau* were sunk by a British force of the battlecruisers HMS *Invincible* and HMS *Inflexible*, three armoured cruisers and two light cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The German armored cruisers were too slow to outrun their pursuers, and their initially accurate gunnery failed to inflict serious damage on the British battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The British 12-inch guns turned the tide of battle once they started scoring hits on the Germans, and the German armored cruisers were fatally crippled before they had a chance to close the range and use their superior secondary armament.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] This victory seemed to validate Lord "Jacky" Fisher's justification in building battlecruisers—to track down and destroy armored cruisers with vessels possessing superior speed and firepower.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The German force commander Admiral Maximilian von Spee had been wary of the Allies' battlecruisers, especially the Imperial Japanese Navy and the Royal Australian Navy—in fact he described the latter's flagship, the battlecruiser HMAS *Australia*, as being superior to his entire force by itself.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] At the Falklands, he had already deduced the battle was lost when he missed the chance to attack the British battlecruisers in port.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] During the Battle of Dogger Bank, *Blücher* was crippled by a shell from a British battlecruiser, which slowed *Blücher* to 17 knots and eventually sealed her fate.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Admiral Franz von Hipper chose to let *Blücher* go down so his more valuable battlecruisers could escape.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] HMS *Warrior*, HMS *Defence* and HMS *Black Prince* were lost at the Battle of Jutland when they inadvertently came into sight and range of the German Navy's battle line, which included several battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The armor belt was shown to be far less than required to survive the 280mm (11 inch) and 300 mm (12 inch) shells of more modern dreadnoughts and battlecruisers and the cruisers were too slow to get away from them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The final nail in the coffin for the armored cruiser type was in the development of capped armor-piercing shells.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Harvey and Krupp Cemented armor that had looked to offer protection failed when hit with soft capped AP shells of large enough size.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Later hard capped AP shell would only make the matter worse.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] After the end of World War I, many of the surviving armored cruisers were sold for scrap.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Washington Naval Treaty of 1922 placed strict limits on the numbers of "capital ships" possessed by the navies of the great powers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] A "capital ship" was defined as any vessel of over 10,000 tons displacement or with guns over 8-in caliber, and several more armored cruisers were decommissioned to comply with the terms of the treaty.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The London Naval Treaty of 1930 introduced further limits on cruiser tonnage, and the former role of the armored cruiser was occupied by more modern light cruisers and heavy cruisers (and, in the case of the German navy, panzerschiffe).
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Hellenic Navy's *Georgios Averof*, constructed in 1909, served with the British Navy as a convoy escort in the Indian Ocean after the fall of Greece, while a number of Japanese armored cruisers were still active as minelayers or training vessels.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Imperial Japanese Navy armored cruisers *Asama*, *Izumo*, *Tokiwa*, *Iwate*, *Yakumo*, *Azuma*, & *Kasuga* were used as training, support, and anti-aircraft ships during the war near the Japanese home islands.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Most were sunk by Allied bombings in Japanese harbors.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Regia Marina's *San Giorgio* was deployed to Spain to protected Italian interests during the Spanish Civil War.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] During World War II, she was heavily utilized at the Siege of Tobruk.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] There she provided anti-aircraft cover and naval gunfire support to Italian units.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] She was heavily damaged by British aircraft and was scuttled to prevent her capture.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Her sister ship, *San Marco* was decommissioned in 1931 and used as a radio controlled target ship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] In 1943, she was scuttled to prevent her capture by the Germans.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The United States Navy's USS *Rochester*, decommissioned since 1933, was moored in Subic Bay and used as a receiving ship and anti-aircraft platform.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] She was later scuttled to prevent her capture by the Japanese during the Invasion of The Philippines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Argentine Navy's ARA *General Belgrano* and ARA *Pueyrredón* served until 1947 and 1954 respectfully.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Swedish Navy's HSwMS *Fylgia* underwent an extensive modernization from 1939 to 1940 and conducted neutrality patrols in the Baltic Sea during World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The only armored cruiser still considered to be in existence, as well as in active duty, is the aforementioned *Georgios Averof*, preserved as a museum in Palaio Faliro, Greece.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruiser was not a close ancestor of heavy cruisers, even though the name might suggest this.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The armored cruiser type had come about in a time of transition as one technology after another presented itself.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Boilers had become better (though still in need of improvement), and Krupp cemented armor and compound steam engines had arrived.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The rate of change was nothing less than staggering and any ship more than 20 years old was found to be completely obsolete.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] The Italian Navy, unable to afford battleships, produced the *Garibaldi*-class cruiser of 7,500 tons displacement which was an international success.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] White DNC of the British Royal Navy was taken by the design and presented the design for the *Cressy*-class cruiser of 12,000 tons displacement designed from the onset as an adjunct to the pre-dreadnought battle line, on 3 May 1897.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] As such the armored cruiser is the direct predecessor of and inspiration for the battlecruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] There were also important technical differences between the heavy cruiser and the armored cruiser, some of which reflected the generational gap between them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Heavy cruisers were typically powered by oil-fired superheated steam boilers and steam turbine engines, and were capable of far faster speeds than armored cruisers (propelled by coal-fired reciprocating steam engines of their era) ever had been.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Countries withdrawing from the Washington Treaty and the London Naval Treaty of 1930 and Second London Naval Treaty 1936 eventually rendered all limitations on heavy cruisers moot, although the only supersized or large cruisers actually built were the two members of the *Alaska* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] Armored cruisers were often pressed into the main line of battle against battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships (battles of the Falkland Islands, Dogger Bank and Jutland).
[src:french-ship-gloire/armoured-cruiser] By contrast, heavy cruisers and light cruisers were not expected to be deployed as such, although there had been some notable engagements (battles of the Denmark Strait, Matapan, Guadalcanal and Surigao Strait).
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] A **battleship** is a large, heavily armored warship with a main battery consisting of large guns, designed to serve as a capital ship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] From their advent in the late 1880s, battleships were among the largest and most formidable warship types ever built, until they were surpassed by aircraft carriers beginning in the 1940s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The modern battleship traces its origin to the sailing ship of the line, which was developed into the steam ship of the line and soon thereafter the ironclad warship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] After a period of extensive experimentation in the 1870s and 1880s, ironclad design was largely standardized by the British *Royal Sovereign* class, which are usually referred to as the first "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] These ships carried an armament that usually included four large guns and several medium-caliber guns that were to be used against enemy battleships, and numerous small guns for self-defense.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Naval powers around the world built dozens of pre-dreadnoughts in the 1890s and early 1900s, though they saw relatively little combat; only two major wars were fought during the period that included pre-dreadnought battles: the Spanish–American War in 1898 and the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The following year, the British launched the revolutionary all-big-gun battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This ship discarded the medium-caliber guns in exchange for a uniform armament of ten large guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] All other major navies quickly began (or had already started) "dreadnoughts" of their own, leading to a major naval arms race.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] During World War I, only one major fleet engagement took place: the Battle of Jutland in 1916, but neither side was able to achieve a decisive result.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the Interwar period, the major naval powers concluded a series of agreements beginning with the Washington Naval Treaty that imposed limits on battleship building to stop a renewed arms race.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] During this period, relatively few battleships were built, but advances in technology led to the maturation of the fast battleship concept, and several of these ships were built in the 1930s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The treaty system eventually broke down after Japan refused to sign the Second London Naval Treaty in 1936.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Although the rise of the aircraft carrier during World War II largely relegated battleships to secondary duties, they still saw significant action during that conflict.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Notable engagements include the battles of Cape Spartivento and Cape Matapan in 1940 and 1941, respectively; the sortie by the German battleship *Bismarck* in 1941; the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in 1942; and the Battle of Leyte Gulf in 1944.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] After World War II, most battleships were placed in reserve, broken up, or used as target ships, and few saw significant active service during the Cold War.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The four American *Iowa*-class battleships were reactivated during the Korean War in the early 1950s and again in the 1980s as part of the 600-ship Navy.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Even at the height of their dominance of naval combat, some strategists questioned the usefulness of battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Beginning in the mid-1880s, the *Jeune École* (Young School) argued that construction of expensive capital ships should stop in favor of cheap cruisers and torpedo boats.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Despite a period of popularity for the *Jeune École*, the idea fell out of favor and the battleship remained the arbiter of naval combat until World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Even afterward, they remained potent symbols of a country's might and they retained significant psychological and diplomatic effects.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] A number of battleships—predominantly American—remain as museum ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] A ship of the line was a large, unarmored wooden sailing ship which mounted a battery of up to 120 smoothbore guns and carronades, which came to prominence with the adoption of line of battle tactics in the early 17th century.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] From 1794, the alternative term 'line of battle ship' was contracted to 'battle ship' or 'battleship'.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The sheer number of guns fired broadside meant a ship of the line could wreck any wooden enemy, holing her hull, knocking down masts, wrecking her rigging, and killing her crew.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] They also imparted a psychological effect on the crews of smaller vessels.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Ships of the line were also fairly resilient to the guns of the day; for example, the British Royal Navy lost no first-rate (the largest type of ship of the line) to enemy action during the entire 18th century.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Over time, ships of the line gradually became larger and carried more guns, but otherwise remained quite similar.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Development of the first-rates was particularly conservative, as these ships represented a major investment.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By the early 1800s, the traditional "seventy-four" (so-named because it carried 74 guns) was no longer considered to be a proper ship of the line, having been supplanted by 84- and 120-gun ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The first major change to the ship of the line concept was the introduction of steam power as an auxiliary propulsion system.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Steam power was gradually introduced to the navy in the first half of the 19th century, initially for small craft and later for frigates.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Early vessels used paddle wheels for propulsion, but by the 1840s, the first screw propeller equipped vessels began to appear.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The value of these smaller steam-powered warships demonstrated their worth, when vessels like the British *Nemesis* proved to be critical to the Anglo-French success in the First Opium War in the 1840s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The French Navy introduced steam to the line of battle with the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850—the first true steam battleship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] *Napoléon*, which was designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme, was armed as a conventional ship-of-the-line, but her steam engines could give her a speed of 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph), regardless of the wind.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This was a potentially decisive advantage in a naval engagement.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The introduction of steam accelerated the growth in size of battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] France and the United Kingdom were the only countries to develop fleets of wooden, steam-screw battleships although several other navies operated small numbers of screw battleships, including Russia (9), the Ottoman Empire (3), Sweden (2), Naples (1), Denmark (1) and Austria (1).
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Concurrent with the development of steam power, another major technological step heralded the end of the traditional ship of the line: guns capable of firing explosive shells.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Pioneering work was done by the French artillery officer Henri-Joseph Paixhans beginning in 1809.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The American artillerist George Bomford followed not far behind, designing the first shell-firing Columbiad in 1812.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The British and Russians began to follow suit in the 1830s, though early smoothbore guns could not fire shells as far as solid shot, which hampered widespread adoption in any fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By the early 1840s, the French Paixhans gun and American Dahlgren gun had begun to be adopted by their respective navies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the Crimean War of 1853–1855, six Russian ships of the line and two frigates of the Black Sea Fleet destroyed seven Turkish frigates and three corvettes with explosive shells at the Battle of Sinop in 1853.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The battle was widely seen as vindication of the shell gun.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Despite losing her bowsprit and her foremast, and being set on fire, she was ready for action again the very next day.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] As amply demonstrated at the Battle of Sinop, and again during the Anglo-French blockade of Sevastopol from 1854 to 1855, wooden ships had become vulnerable to shell-firing guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This prompted the French emperor Napoleon III to order the first ironclad warships: the *Dévastation*-class ironclad floating batterys.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Three of these ships led the Anglo-French attack on the Russian fortress on the Kinburn Peninsula in the Battle of Kinburn in 1855, where they bore the brunt of Russian artillery fire, but were not seriously damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The success of these ships prompted the French and British to order several similar vessels.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In March 1858, the French took development of the ironclad to its next logical step: a proper, ocean-going armored warship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This vessel, another design by Dupuy de Lome, was *Gloire*, and after her launching in 1859, Napoleon III ordered another five similar ships, which sparked a naval arms race with Britain.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The first French ironclads had the profile of a ship of the line, cut to one deck due to weight considerations.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Although made of wood and reliant on sail for most journeys, *Gloire* and her contemporaries were fitted with screw propellers, and their wooden hulls were protected by a layer of thick iron armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Britain responded promptly with *Warrior*, a similar but much larger ironclad with an iron hull.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By the time *Warrior* was completed in 1861, another nine ironclads were under construction in British shipyards, some of which were conversions of screw ships of the line that were already being built.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Spain and Russia ordered ironclads in 1861, as did the United States and rebel Confederate States of America after the start of the American Civil War.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Construction of these large and expensive warships remained controversial until March 1862, when news of the Battle of Hampton Roads, fought between the Union USS *Monitor* and the Confederate CSS *Virginia*, firmly settled debate in favor of even larger construction programs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] From the 1860s to 1880s, navies experimented with the positioning of guns, in turrets, central-batteries, or barbettes; ironclads of the period also prominently used the ram as a principal weapon.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] As steam technology developed, masts were gradually removed from battleship designs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The British Chief Constructor, Edward Reed, produced the *Devastation*-class ironclads in 1869.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] These were mastless turret ships, which adopted twin-screw propulsion and an arrangement of two pairs of 12-inch (305 mm) guns, one fore and one aft of the superstructure, that prefigured the advent of the pre-dreadnought battleship some two decades later.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By the mid-1870s steel was used as a construction material alongside iron and wood.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The French Navy's *Redoutable*, laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876, was a combination central battery and barbette ship, which became the first capital ship in the world to use steel as the principal building material.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The rapid pace of technological developments, particularly in terms of gun capabilities and thickness of armor to combat them, quickly rendered ships obsolescent.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the continuous attempt by gun manufacturers to keep ahead of developments in armor plate, larger and larger guns were fitted to many of the later ironclads.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Some of these, such as the British *Victoria* class, carried guns as large as 16.25 inches (413 mm) in diameter, while the Italian *Duilio*-class ironclads were armed with colossal 17.7-inch (450 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the 1880s, opposition to fleets of large, expensive ironclads arose around the world, but most notably in France, where a group of naval officers led by Admiral Théophile Aube formed the *Jeune École* (Young School).
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The theory, which held as one of its core tenets that small, cheap torpedo boats could easily defeat ironclads, was based on combat experience during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The doctrine also posited that modern steel-hulled cruisers could defeat a more powerful navy by attacking the country's merchant shipping, rather than engage in a direct battle.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The concept proved to be highly influential for several years, shaping the construction programs of France, Germany, Italy, and Austria-Hungary, among others throughout the world.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In 1889, the British government passed the Naval Defence Act 1889, which embarked on a major naval construction program aimed at establishing the so-called two-power standard, whereby the Royal Navy would be stronger than the next two largest navies combined.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The plan saw the construction of the eight *Royal Sovereign*-class battleships, which have been regarded as the first class of battleship that would retrospectively be referred to as "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] These large battleships incorporated a number of major improvements over earlier vessels like the *Devastation*s, including a high freeboard for true ocean-going capability, more extensive armor protection, heavier secondary battery guns, and greater speed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The ships were armed with four 13.5 in (340 mm) guns in two twin mounts, fore and aft, which established the pattern for subsequent battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] After building a trio of smaller second class battleships intended for the colonial empire, Britain followed with the nine-strong *Majestic*-class battleships in 1893–1895, which improved on the basic *Royal Sovereign* design.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] These ships adopted the 12 in (305 mm) gun, which would become the standard for all subsequent British pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Foreign navies quickly began pre-dreadnoughts of their own; France began *Brennus* in 1889 and Germany laid down four *Brandenburg*-class battleships in 1890.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The United States Navy laid down three *Indiana*-class battleships in 1891, the same year work began on the Russian battleship *Tri Sviatitelia*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Japan ordered the two *Fuji*-class battleships from British yards, to an improved *Royal Sovereign* design, in 1894.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Navy eventually ordered its own pre-dreadnoughts, beginning with the *Habsburg* class in 1899.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] All of these ships carried guns of between 11 and 13.4 in (280 and 340 mm), save the Austro-Hungarian vessels, which, being significantly smaller than the rest, only carried 9.4 in (240 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] They also generally carried a light armament for defense against torpedo boats and other light craft.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Some ships varied from this general pattern, such as the American *Indiana*s, which carried a heavier secondary battery of 8-inch (203 mm) guns, and the German *Brandenburg*s, which had six 11-inch guns for instead of the usual four heavy guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Many of the early French pre-dreadnoughts, such as *Charles Martel*, carried a mixed heavy armament of two 12-inch and two 10.8-inch (274 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnoughts continued the technical innovations of the ironclad throughout the 1890s and early 1900s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Compound armor gave way to much stronger Harvey armor developed in the United States in 1890, which was in turn superseded by the German Krupp armor in 1894.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] As armor became stronger, it could be reduced in thickness considerably, which saved weight that could be allocated to other aspects of the ship design, and generally permitted larger and more capable battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] At the same time, the advent of smokeless powder continued the trend begun in the French navy of comparatively smaller guns firing at higher velocities.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Early on in the pre-dreadnought era, most navies standardized on the 12-inch gun; only Germany remained the significant outlier, relying on 11-inch and even 9.4-inch guns for its pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Similarly, later in the pre-dreadnought era, the secondary batteries grew in caliber, usually to 7 to 8 in (178 to 203 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the last years of the 19th century and the first years of the 20th, the escalation in the building of battleships became an arms race between Britain and Germany.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The German naval laws of 1890 and 1898 authorized a fleet of 38 battleships, a vital threat to the balance of naval power.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Britain answered with further shipbuilding, but by the end of the pre-dreadnought era, British supremacy at sea had markedly weakened.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In 1883, the United Kingdom had 38 ironclad battleships, twice as many as France and almost as many as the rest of the world put together.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In 1897, Britain's lead was far smaller due to competition from France, Germany, and Russia, as well as the development of pre-dreadnought fleets in Italy, the United States and Japan.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Ottoman Empire, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands, Chile, and Brazil all had second-rate fleets led by armored cruisers, coastal defence ships or monitors.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnought battleships received their first test in combat in the Spanish–American War in 1898 at the Battle of Santiago de Cuba.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] An American squadron that included four pre-dreadnoughts had blockaded a Spanish squadron of four armored cruisers in Santiago de Cuba until 3 July, when the Spanish ships attempted to break through and escape.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] All four cruisers were destroyed in the ensuing engagement, as were a pair of Spanish destroyers, and the American ships received little damage in return.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The battle seemed to indicate that the mixed batteries of pre-dreadnought battleships were very effective, as the medium-caliber guns had inflicted most of the damage (which reinforced the observations of the Battle of Manila Bay, where only cruisers armed with medium guns had been present).
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] It also led navies around the world to begin working on better solutions for rangefinding in the hope of improving gunnery at longer ranges.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Conflicting colonial ambitions in Korea and Manchuria led Russia and Japan to the next major use of pre-dreadnoughts in combat.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] During the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905, squadrons of battleships engaged in a number of battles, including the Battle of the Yellow Sea and the Battle of Tsushima.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Naval mines also proved to be a deadly threat to battleships on both sides, sinking the Russian *Petropavlovsk* in March 1904 and the Japanese battleships *Hatsuse* and *Yashima* on the same day in May.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The action in the Yellow Sea began during a Russian attempt to break out of Port Arthur, which the Japanese under Admiral Tōgō Heihachirō had blockaded.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Russians outmaneuvered the Japanese and briefly escaped, but the latter's superior speed allowed them to catch up.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] A 12-inch shell struck the Russian flagship, killing the squadron commander and causing the Russian ships to fall into disarray and retreat back to Port Arthur.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] With night falling, the Japanese broke off and reimposed the blockade.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] At Tsushima, Togo outmaneuvered the Russian Second Pacific Squadron that had been sent to reinforce the Pacific Fleet, and the Japanese battleships quickly inflicted fatal damage with long-range fire from their 12-inch guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In both actions during the Russo-Japanese War, the fleets engaged at longer range (as far as 12,000 yd (11,000 m) at the Yellow Sea), where only their 12-inch guns were effective.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Only in the final stages of the battle at Tsushima, by which time the Russian fleet had been severely damaged and most of its modern battleships sunk or disabled, did the Japanese fleet close to effective range of their secondary guns, fighting as close as 2,700 yd (2,500 m).
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The actions, particularly the decisive engagement at Tsushima, demonstrated that the lessons taken from the Spanish–American War were incorrect, and that the large-caliber gun should be the only offensive weapon carried by battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the early 1900s, some naval theorists had begun to argue for future battleships to discard the heavy secondary batteries and instead carry only big guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The first prominent example was Vittorio Cuniberti, the chief engineer of the Italian *Regia Marina* (Royal Navy); he published an article in 1903 titled "An Ideal Battleship for the British Navy" in *Jane's Fighting Ships*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Japanese Navy was the first to actually order any of these new ships, beginning with the two *Satsuma*-class battleships in 1904, though due to shortages of 12-inch guns, they were completed with a mix of 12- and 10-inch (254 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By early 1905, Fisher had converted to the 12-inch gun for his proposed new capital ships, and in March that year, the German Navy had decided to build an all-big-gun battleship for the planned *Nassau* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The American *South Carolina* class was authorized in 1905, but work did not begin until December 1906.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Though several navies had begun design work on all-big-gun battleships, the first to be completed was the British *Dreadnought*, which had been ordered by Fisher.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] He actually preferred a very large armored cruiser equipped with an all-big-gun armament, which would come to be known as the battlecruiser, and he only included *Dreadnought* in his 1905 construction program to appease naval officers who favored continued battleship building.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Fisher believed that Britain's security against the French and Russian threats would be better guaranteed by squadrons of fast battlecruisers, three of which were laid down in 1906.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Regardless of Fisher's intentions, the rapidly changing strategic calculus invalidated his plans and ensured that when the 1906–1907 program was being debated, Germany would be Britain's primary rival, the Royal Navy chose to build three more dreadnoughts instead of further battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Reactions from the other naval powers was immediate; very few pre-dreadnoughts were built afterward, and in the first seven years of the ensuing arms race, all of the major naval powers either had their own dreadnoughts in service or nearing completion.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Of these competitions, the Anglo-German race was the most significant, though others took place, such as the South American contest.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Even naval powers of the second and third rank, such as Spain; Brazil, Chile, and Argentina in South America; and Greece and the Ottoman Empire in the Mediterranean had begun dreadnought programs, either domestically or ordering abroad.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Technological development continued over the decade that followed *Dreadnought*'s launch.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Already by 1910, the British had begun the first of the so-called "super-dreadnoughts" that carried significantly more powerful 13.5-inch (340 mm) guns, all on the centerline.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The United States followed suit in 1911, though increasing the caliber of their guns to 14 inches (356 mm).
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] France adopted a 13.4 in (340 mm) gun for its *Bretagne*-class battleships, laid down in 1912.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] That year, Japan laid down the first of its *Fusō*-class battleships, also armed with a 14-inch main battery.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Germans waited until 1913, but skipped directly to 15-inch (381 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By this time, Britain had led the way to the 15-inch gun with the *Queen Elizabeth* class begun in late 1912.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] But more importantly than the increase of caliber, the *Queen Elizabeth*s were the first completely oil-fired battleships and the first fast battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] At around the same time, the United States introduced the next major innovation in battleship design: the all or nothing armor system in the *Nevada* class laid down in 1912.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The heaviest possible armor was used to protect the ship's propulsion machinery and ammunition magazines, but intermediate protection was stripped away from non-essential areas, since this mid-weight armor only served to detonate armor-piercing shells.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By the start of World War I in July 1914, the Royal Navy's Grand Fleet outnumbered the German High Seas Fleet by 21 to 13 in numbers of dreadnought battleships and 4 to 3 in battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] And over the course of the war, Britain would add another 14 dreadnoughts, while Germany completed another 6.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] German strategy presumed that Britain would launch an immediate offensive into the southern North Sea, but the British preferred to establish a distant blockade, which very quickly stopped German maritime trade.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Both sides were aware that, because of the greater number of British dreadnoughts, a full fleet engagement would be likely to result in a British victory.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The German strategy was therefore to try to provoke an engagement on their terms: either to induce a part of the Grand Fleet to enter battle alone, or to fight a pitched battle near the German coastline, where friendly minefields, torpedo-boats and submarines could be used to even the odds.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The British fleet commander, Admiral John Jellicoe, refused to be drawn into unfavorable conditions and enforced the blockade at the English Channel and between Scotland and Norway.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the Baltic Sea, Germany found itself in the reverse situation, in an even more lopsided fashion versus its Russian opponent.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Russian Baltic Fleet had only four dreadnoughts at the start of the war, so they adopted a purely defensive approach to guard the capital at Petrograd and the northern flank of the Russian army units fighting on the Eastern Front.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the Mediterranean Sea, Italy initially remained neutral, despite being a member of the Triple Alliance with Germany and Austria-Hungary, leaving the latter to face the French Navy and British Mediterranean Fleet alone.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] After ensuring the French army units in French North Africa were safely convoyed to France, the French fleet sailed to the Adriatic Sea to blockade the Austro-Hungarian fleet, which refused to leave their fortified bases.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The French, like the other major European naval commanders, had failed to consider that their opponents would not concede to engaging in battle on terms unfavorable to them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Adriatic quickly turned into another stalemate as the threat of Austro-Hungarian mines and submarines prevented a more aggressive employment of the French fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Germans embarked on a number of sweeps into the North Sea and raids on British coastal towns to draw out part of the Grand Fleet, which would be isolated and destroyed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] These included the raid on Scarborough, Hartlepool and Whitby, where the Germans nearly caught an isolated British battle squadron, but turned away, thinking that it was the entire Grand Fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This strategy ultimately led to the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, the largest clash of battleship fleets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The first stage of the battle was fought largely by the two sides' battlecruiser squadrons, though the British were supported by four of the *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] After both battleship fleets engaged, the British crossed the Germans' "T" twice, but the latter managed to extricate themselves from the action as darkness fell.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Early on 1 June, the High Seas Fleet had reached port.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the course of the fighting, three British battlecruisers were destroyed, as was one German battlecruiser and the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Numerous cruisers and destroyers were lost on both sides as well.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Germans made two further offensive operations in the months after Jutland.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The first, which led to the inconclusive action of 19 August, saw one German battleship torpedoed by a British submarine and two British cruisers sunk by German U-boats.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This incident convinced the British that the risks posed by submarines were too great to send the Grand Fleet into the southern North Sea, barring exceptional circumstances like a German invasion of Britain.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the second German operation, which took place on 18–19 October, a German cruiser was damaged by a submarine and the Grand Fleet remained in port.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By this time, the Germans were similarly convinced of the futility of their attempts to isolate part of the British fleet, and discontinued such raids.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] They instead turned to unrestricted submarine warfare, which resulted in their battleships being reduced to a supporting force that guarded the U-boat bases.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the Baltic, the Germans made two attempts to capture the islands in the Gulf of Riga.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The first came in August 1915, and in the ensuing Battle of the Gulf of Riga, a pair of German dreadnoughts engaged in an artillery duel at long range with the Russian pre-dreadnought *Slava* guarding the minefields that protected the gulf.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Germans drove off the Russian ship, cleared the minefield, but by the time they entered the gulf, submarines had reportedly arrived.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Unwilling to risk the battleships in the shallow, confined waters of the gulf, the Germans retreated.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The second attempt—Operation Albion—took place in October 1917.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] During the Battle of Moon Sound, another pair of German dreadnoughts damaged *Slava* so badly that she had to be scuttled, and the Germans completed their amphibious assault on the islands.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The modern units of the French and British fleets in the Mediterranean spent much of the war guarding the entrance to the Adriatic, first based at Malta and later moving to Corfu.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] They saw very little action through the war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] For their part, the Italians were content to reinforce the blockading force guarding the Adriatic, as they, too, were unwilling to risk their capital ships in the mine and submarine infested waters of the Austrian Littoral.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Instead, light forces carried out most of the operations.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Meanwhile, several French and British pre-dreadnoughts were sent to attack the Ottoman defenses guarding the Dardanelles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the ensuing naval operations from February to March 1915, several battleships were sunk or damaged by mines and torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] When the fleets failed to break through the defenses, the British and French decided to land at Gallipoli to try to take the fortifications by land; the remaining battleships were thereafter used to provide naval gunfire support.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This, too, ultimately failed and by January 1916, the British and French withdrew their troops.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Russian battleships saw more action in the Black Sea against their Ottoman opponents.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By 1916, the Russians had completed a pair of dreadnoughts in the Black Sea, which severely curtailed Ottoman freedom of maneuver.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the course of the war, older pre-dreadnoughts proved to be highly vulnerable to underwater damage, whether by naval mine or ship-launched or submarine-delivered torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] HMS *Formidable* was sunk by a German U-boat in the English Channel in 1915.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] At the Dardanelles, HMS *Majestic* was sunk by a German U-boat, HMS *Goliath* was sunk by the Ottoman destroyer *Muavenet-i Milliye*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The British *Ocean* and *Irresistible* and the French *Bouvet* were all sunk by mines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] HMS *Russell* and HMS *Cornwallis* were both sunk by mines in the Mediterranean in 1916 and 1917, respectively.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] HMS *King Edward VII* was similarly mined and sunk off the British coast in 1916, and HMS *Britannia* was sunk by a U-boat in the final days of the war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The French *Gaulois* and *Suffren* were sunk by U-boats in 1916, and *Danton* was torpedoed and sunk by a U-boat in 1917.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] At Jutland, the only battleship lost was the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*, which was torpedoed by a destroyer.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In contrast, dreadnoughts proved to be much more resilient to underwater attack.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] HMS *Marlborough* was damaged by a torpedo at Jutland, but nevertheless returned to port.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The German SMS *Westfalen* was torpedoed at the action of 19 August 1916, and SMS *Grosser Kurfürst* and *Kronprinz* were torpedoed by the same submarine in November 1917; all three survived.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] SMS *Bayern* was mined during Operation Albion and remained in action against Russian artillery batteries for some time thereafter.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Dreadnoughts lost to underwater attack were rare.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] HMS *Audacious* was sunk by a mine in October 1914, the Austro-Hungarian SMS *Szent Istvan* was sunk by Italian MAS boats in June 1918, and five months later, Italian frogmen sank *Viribus Unitis* using a powerful limpet mine.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the immediate aftermath of the war, the most modern units of the German fleet was interned at Scapa Flow, where in June 1919, their crews scuttled the fleet to avoid it being handed over to the Allies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The remaining dreadnoughts still in German ports were therefore seized as compensation for the scuttled ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The postwar *Reichsmarine* of Weimar Germany was limited to a contingent of eight old pre-dreadnoughts (of which two would be kept in reserve) under the terms of the Treaty of Versailles; new battleships were subject to severe restrictions on size and armament.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The surviving battleships of Austria-Hungary, the other defeated Central Power, were soon distributed among the Allies, to be broken up.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] While the other major naval powers remained free to build new battleships, most of them were financially crippled after the war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The prospect of a renewed naval arms race between the United States, United Kingdom, and Japan, appealed to few politicians in the three countries, and so they concluded the Washington Naval Treaty in 1922, which also included Italy and France.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The treaty limited the number and size of battleships, and imposed a ten-year building holiday, along with other provisions.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The treaty also imposed a ratio of 5:5:3 on total displacement of battleships for the US, UK, and Japan, respectively, and it severed the Anglo-Japanese Alliance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The only exceptions to the building holiday were for the two British *Nelson*-class battleships, which were permitted to give Britain parity with the latest American and Japanese battleships, which were all armed with 16-inch (406 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Washington treaty was followed by a series of other naval treaties, including the First London Naval Treaty (1930) and the Second London Naval Treaty (1936), which both set additional limits on major warships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The treaty limitations meant that fewer new battleships were launched in 1919–1939 than in 1905–1914.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The treaties also inhibited development by imposing upper limits on the weights of ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Designs like the projected British N3-class battleship, the first American *South Dakota* class, and the Japanese *Kii* class—all of which continued the trend to larger ships with bigger guns and thicker armor—never got off the drawing board.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Those designs which were commissioned during this period were referred to as treaty battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The collapse of the treaty system began during the negotiations for the Second London Treaty, where Japan demanded parity with Britain and the US, which the latter two flatly rejected.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Japan withdrew from the treaty system in 1936, though the agreements remained in effect until January 1937.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] As early as 1914, the British Admiral Percy Scott predicted that battleships would soon be made irrelevant by aircraft.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Between 1916 and 1918, US Admiral William Fullam published a series of papers stating that aircraft would become an independent strike arm of the fleet, and argued that the *Lexington*-class battlecruisers then under construction should be converted to aircraft carriers than scrapped.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By the end of World War I, aircraft had successfully adopted the torpedo as a weapon.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In 1921 the Italian general and air theorist Giulio Douhet completed a hugely influential treatise on strategic bombing titled *The Command of the Air*, which foresaw the dominance of air power over conventional military and naval forces.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In 1921, US General Billy Mitchell used the ex-German dreadnought SMS *Ostfriesland* in a series of bombing tests conducted by the Navy and Army.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The test involved a series of attacks on the stationary, unmanned ships using low-level, land-based bombers dropping bombs that ranged from 550 to 2,000 pounds (250 to 910 kg).
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] *Ostfriesland* was sunk by the heaviest bombs, though Mitchell broke the rules of the tests and the subsequent report concluded that had the ship been crewed, underway, and firing back at the aircraft, damage control teams aboard *Ostfriesland* could have managed any damage inflicted.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Mitchell and his supporters nevertheless embarked on a public campaign that falsely claimed that *Ostfriesland* was a super-battleship, and the quick sinking proved that battleships were obsolete.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Mitchell would eventually be subjected to a court martial, convicted, and discharged from the Army over his insubordinate tactics.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Naval aviation traces its origin back to the first decade of the 20th century, though early efforts were based on using aircraft to scout for the fleet and help direct gunfire at long range.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] A number of experimental aircraft carriers were employed during World War I, primarily by the Royal Navy, all converted from merchant vessels or existing warships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The US Navy completed its first carrier, USS *Langley*, in 1922.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] But aircraft carriers in the 1920s faced a number of challenges to be overcome: aircraft of the day were short-ranged, which meant the carrier had to be very close to the enemy to be able to launch and then recover a strike, which exposed the carriers to attack.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In addition, the available planes had insufficient power to carry meaningful bomb loads.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Early naval aviators nevertheless pioneered effective tactics like dive bombing during this period.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Because the Washington Treaty system precluded the construction of any new battleships until the early 1930s, the major naval powers began a program of modernization for their most effective battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Britain conducted a series of refits to their *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships through the 1920s, adding anti-torpedo bulges, additional anti-aircraft guns, and aircraft catapults; further refits in the 1930s increased armor protection and further strengthened their anti-aircraft batteries.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The *Revenge*-class battleships were less heavily modified during the period.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The US *Florida*, *Wyoming* class, and *New York* classes received similar treatments in the 1920s, while the *Nevada* and *Pennsylvania* classes received new turbines, additional armor, and more anti-aircraft guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Japanese similarly updated their *Fusō*, *Ise*, and *Nagato*-class battleships, and rebuilt three of the four *Kongō*-class battlecruisers into fast battleships, albeit with significantly inferior protection compared to the other ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] They all also received distinctive pagoda masts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] *Hiei* was initially disarmed to serve as a training ship under the terms of the Washington Treaty, but was remilitarized in the late 1930s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In the 1930s, all four classes were lengthened and had their propulsion systems improved to increase their speeds.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The French and Italian navies were exempted from the 10-year building holiday, owing to the comparative obsolescence of their battleships; they were permitted to build 70,000 long tons (71,000 t) worth of battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] But the weak economies of both countries led both to defer new construction until Germany began building the *Deutschland* class of heavily armed cruiser at the end of the 1920s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This prompted the French to build the *Dunkerque* class of small, fast battleships armed with 13 in (330 mm) guns, which led to a short arms race in Europe in the mid-1930s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Italians responded with the significantly larger and more powerful *Littorio* class, armed with 15-inch guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The French, in turn, began the *Richelieu*-class battleships to counter the *Littorio*s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] By this time, Nazi Germany had signed the Anglo-German Naval Agreement in 1935, which removed the restrictions imposed by Versailles and pegged German naval strength to 35% of British tonnage.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] This permitted the construction of two *Scharnhorst*-class battleships, which were also a response to the *Dunkerque*s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The advent of the *Richelieu*s prompted the Germans to build the two *Bismarck*-class battleships late in the decade.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The Germans thereafter embarked on the ambitious Plan Z naval construction program, which included a total of eight battleships, of which the *Bismarck*s would be the first two.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] Against the backdrop of European rearmament in the mid-1930s, Britain began planning its first battleship class in a decade: the *King George V* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] These were armed with 14-inch guns intended to comply with the terms of the Second London Naval Conference, and they were laid down in 1937.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] The United States began their *North Carolina* class at the same time, and though they were intended to be armed with 14-inch guns, Japan's refusal to agree to the Second London Treaty led the US to invoke a clause of the treaty that allowed an increase to 16-inch guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] In 1939, these were followed by the four *South Dakota*-class battleships, and in 1940 by the first of four *Iowa*-class battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p01] For its part, Japan had decided to embark on a program of four very large *Yamato*-class battleships, armed with 18-inch (457 mm) guns, as early as 1934, though work did not begin on the first ship until late 1937.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The German pre-dreadnought *Schleswig-Holstein* fired the first shots of World War II by initiating the bombardment of the Polish garrison at Westerplatte in the early hours on 1 September 1939.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The German *Scharnhorst*-class battleships caught the British carrier HMS *Glorious* off the coast of Norway and sank her during the Norwegian campaign.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] In the former action, the British sank a pair of older *Bretagne*-class battleships and the fast battleship *Dunkerque*, though the latter was refloated and repaired.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] At Dakar, the French battleship *Richelieu* and other forces fended off the British task force, which resulted in the torpedoing of the battleship HMS *Resolution*, which was severely damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Italy entered the war in June 1940, shortly before the French defeat.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] In November, the British launched a nighttime airstrike on the naval base at Taranto; in the Battle of Taranto, Fairey Swordfish torpedo bombers disabled three Italian battleships, though they were subsequently repaired.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Over the next year, Italian and British battleships engaged in a number of inconclusive actions as they contested the supply lines to North Africa.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] These included the Battle of Cape Spartivento in November 1940 and the Battle of Cape Matapan in March 1941.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] At Matapan, the battleship *Vittorio Veneto* was badly damaged by a Swordfish, though the ship returned to port.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The British battleships *Valiant*, *Warspite*, and *Barham* nevertheless caught a group of three heavy cruisers that evening and destroyed them in a furious, close-range night action.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Convoy battles continued through 1941 and into 1942, with actions such as First and Second Sirte.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] By 1943, Italian operations were sharply reduced due to a shortage of fuel, and after the Allied invasion of Italy, the country surrendered, allowing most of its fleet to be interned at Malta.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] While on the way, the battleship *Roma* was sunk by a German Fritz X guided glide bomb.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] In the meantime, in January 1941, the Germans began to send their few battleships on commerce raiding operations in the Atlantic, starting with the two *Scharnhorst*-class ships in Operation Berlin, which was not particularly successful.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Bismarck* followed with Operation Rheinübung in May, which resulted in two actions, the Battle of the Denmark Strait and the sinking of *Bismarck*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] During the operation, *Bismarck* was crippled by Swordfish torpedo bombers, which allowed a pair of British battleships to catch and destroy her.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] By 1942, the last operational German battleships—*Tirpitz* and *Scharnhorst*—were sent to occupied Norway to serve as a fleet in being to tie down British naval resources and to attack supply convoys to the Soviet Union.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The battleship HMS *Duke of York* eventually sank *Scharnhorst* at the Battle of North Cape in December 1943, and *Tirpitz* was destroyed by British heavy bombers in 1944.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] On 7 December 1941, the Japanese launched a surprise attack on the US naval base at Pearl Harbor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Over the course of two waves of dive-, level- and torpedo bombers, the Japanese sank or destroyed five battleships and inflicted serious damage to the facilities there.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Three days later, land-based Japanese aircraft operating out of French Indochina, then occupied by Japan, caught and sank the British battleship HMS *Prince of Wales* and the battlecruiser HMS *Repulse* off the coast of British Malaya.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Though the Taranto and Pearl Harbor strikes were significant steps toward aircraft replacing the battleship as the primary naval striking arm, the sinking of *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* marked the first time aircraft had sunk capital ships that were maneuvering and returning fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Employment of battleships during the Pacific War was limited by a number of factors.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Japanese strategic doctrine, the *Kantai Kessen*, envisioned a decisive clash of battleships at the end of the war, and so kept most of their battleships in home waters, and only the four *Kongō*s were routinely detached to escort the aircraft carriers of the *Kido Butai*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] For their part, the US kept its surviving pre-war battleships out of action primarily because they were too slow to keep up with the carriers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Later in the war, they were employed as coastal bombardment vessels.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Nevertheless, American and Japanese battleships saw significant action during the Guadalcanal campaign in 1942, most notably at the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] There, an American squadron centered on the battleships *Washington* and *South Dakota* intercepted and sank the battleship *Kirishima*, though *South Dakota* received significant damage in return.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] As more and more of the American fast battleships entered service from 1942, onward, they were frequently used as escorts for the fast carrier task force that was the US Navy's primary striking arm in its campaign across the central Pacific.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] During the Philippines campaign, battleships played a central role during the Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The action was one of the largest naval battles in history, which took place over several days and as three Japanese fleets attacked the Allied invasion fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The Japanese battleship *Musashi*, part of Center Force, was sunk by American carrier aircraft during the Battle of Sibuyan Sea on 24 October.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Surigao Strait the following night, several US battleships that had been repaired from the attack on Pearl Harbor defeated the Japanese Southern Force that included a pair of battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Center Force attacked again on 25 October in the Battle off Samar, but was driven off by destroyers and aircraft from several escort carriers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Okinawa in April 1945, Japan sent *Yamato* as a final suicide mission to attack the landing beaches and attempt to stop the invasion of the island.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] American aircraft scored between nine and thirteen torpedo hits and six bomb hits on the ship and sank her.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Haruna* was sunk by US aircraft off Kure, Japan, in July.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The war ended with the Japanese surrender aboard the battleship USS *Missouri* in September 1945.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] After World War II, several navies retained their existing battleships, but most were either placed in their reserve fleets or scrapped outright.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Of their surviving pre-war battleships, most of the American vessels were either scrapped or sunk as target ships by 1948, though the most modern vessels, those of the *Tennessee* and *Maryland* classes, survived until the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] One of the earlier vessels, USS *Texas*, was preserved as a museum ship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The four *King George V*-class ships were all broken up by 1957, Only two battleships—the British HMS *Vanguard* and the French *Jean Bart*—were completed after the war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Vanguard* did not long outlast the *King George V*s, being scrapped herself in 1960.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Jean Bart* (and her sister *Richelieu*) remained in the French fleet's inventory until the early 1960s, when they were discarded.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Three of the six American *North Carolina*- and *South Dakota*-class ships were similarly scrapped in the early 1960s, but the other three—*North Carolina*, *Massachusetts*, and *Alabama*—were retained as museum ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] With the reduced naval budgets of the immediate postwar period, the US Navy chose to concentrate its resources on its carrier force.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Besides the rise of aircraft carriers as the preeminent naval striking force, the advent of nuclear weapons influenced the decision to abandon large battleship fleets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] In 1946, *Nagato*, which was seized by the US, and four American battleships were used during the Operation Crossroads nuclear weapons tests, though three of the American ships survived the two blasts and were later sunk with conventional weapons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Of the remaining, smaller battleships fleets, Italy retained its two *Andrea Doria*-class battleships, of 1913 vintage, until the late 1950s and early 1960s, when they were scrapped.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] One other battleship, *Giulio Cesare* was taken by the Soviets as reparations and renamed *Novorossiysk*; she was sunk by a mine in the Black Sea on 29 October 1955.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The two surviving *Littorio*-class ships were taken by the US and UK as war reparations and scrapped in the late 1940s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The Soviets still had a pair of World War I-era battleships—*Parizhskaya Kommuna* and *Gangut*—but they, too, were scrapped in the late 1950s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The three large South American navies still had a handful of pre-World War I dreadnoughts in service after the war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Brazil eventually discarded its two *Minas Gerais*-class battleships in the early 1950s; *Argentina* sold its two *Rivadavia*-class battleships in 1956; the last ship in the region, the Chilean *Almirante Latorre*, followed them to the breakers' yard in 1959.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The four *Iowa*-class battleships were the only vessels of the type to see significant combat after World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] All four ships were reactivated for gunfire support duties during the Korean War in the early 1950s, and *New Jersey* was also deployed during the Vietnam War in 1968–1969 for the same task.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] All four ships were modernized in the early 1980s with Tomahawk cruise missiles, Harpoon anti-ship missiles, and Phalanx CIWS systems, along with the latest radar systems.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] They were recommissioned as part of the 600-ship Navy program under President Ronald Reagan.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *New Jersey* next saw action in 1982, bombarding Syrian artillery during the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* took part in Operation Desert Storm against Iraqi forces in 1991, bombarding enemy positions along the coast.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The ships proved to be expensive to operate, and they required thousands of men to keep in service, so *Iowa* and *New Jersey* were already back in reserve by that time, and *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* were also decommissioned by the end of 1991.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] All four were struck from the Naval Vessel Register in 1995.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] When the last *Iowa*-class ship was finally stricken from the Naval Vessel Registry, no battleships remained in service or in reserve with any navy worldwide.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] A number are preserved as museum ships, either afloat or in drydock.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The U.S. has eight battleships on display: *Massachusetts*, *North Carolina*, *Alabama*, *Iowa*, *New Jersey*, *Missouri*, *Wisconsin*, and *Texas*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *New Jersey* are museums at Pearl Harbor and Camden, New Jersey, respectively.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Iowa* is on display as an educational attraction at the Los Angeles Waterfront in San Pedro, California.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Wisconsin* now serves as a museum ship in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Massachusetts*, which has the distinction of never having lost a man during service, is on display at the Battleship Cove naval museum in Fall River, Massachusetts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Texas*, the first battleship turned into a museum, is normally on display at the San Jacinto Battleground State Historic Site, near Houston, but as of 2021 is closed for repairs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *North Carolina* is on display in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] *Alabama* is on display in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The USS Arizona Memorial was erected over the wreck of *Arizona*, which was sunk during the Pearl Harbor attack in 1941, to commemorate those killed in the raid.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Memorials were also placed to mark the wreck of *Utah*, also sunk during the attack.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The only other 20th-century battleship on display is the Japanese pre-dreadnought *Mikasa*, preserved since 1923.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] On 22 December 2025, the United States Navy announced the planned construction of new battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The Trump class will be the first nuclear-powered battleship, and it is planned to carry nuclear-capable cruise missiles, and conventional weapons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] For much of their existence, battleships were the embodiment of sea power.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The American naval officer Alfred Thayer Mahan argued in his seminal 1890 work, *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*, a strong navy was vital to the success of a nation, and control of the seas was a prerequisite for the projection of force.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Conversely, countries with weak navies would inevitably decline.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Mahan argued that the cruiser warfare advocated by the *Jeune Ecole* could never be decisive, and that only fleets of battleships could control sea lanes and enforce blockades of an enemy's coast.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The book proved to be widely influential across the world's navies; it was translated into German in 1896, where it was used to support the German naval expansion program championed by Alfred von Tirpitz.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] A Japanese-language translation also appeared in 1896, and it soon became required reading at the Japanese naval academy.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] By the end of the decade, Russian, French, Italian, and Spanish versions were produced.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The "fleet in being" in part acts as a deterrent against attack.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The concept underpinned Tirpitz's so-called "risk theory" that was the basis of his program to build a German battle fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Even if the Royal Navy maintained a numerical superiority, the risk that the German fleet would inflict grievous damage even in the case of a British victory would militate against any such battle taking place, and Germany would be free to pursue its global ambitions.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, naval tacticians had developed a number of formations in which to employ battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The most prominent were referred to as "line ahead" and "line abreast".
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The former, the standard tactic during the age of sail, arrayed ships in a single-file line, which emphasized broadside fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The latter placed ships side-by-side, which was suited to close-range melees where ramming and torpedoes could be effectively employed; after Tegetthoff's success at Lissa in 1866 used a modified line abreast formation, the tactic enjoyed a period of popularity for several years.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] By the 1880s, line-ahead tactics had returned to prominence.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Royal Navy officers devised the tactic referred to as "crossing the T" of an enemy fleet, whereby one fleet steaming in line-ahead formation crossed in front of another line of battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] This maneuver would allow one's own battleships to concentrate entire broadsides on the leading enemy ship, while one's opponent could only reply with their forward guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Many navies adopted the tactic soon thereafter.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] As the threat of underwater attack, including mines and torpedoes, developed after the 1860s, capital ships could no longer maintain close blockades of enemy ports.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] This required smaller, faster scouts to observe hostile ports so that an enemy fleet could be brought to battle.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Modern cruisers began to be built in the 1880s for this purpose.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Almost immediately after the invention of the airplane, navies recognized its potential as a reconnaissance unit for the fleet's battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The Austro-Hungarian Navy, then following the *Jeune École* doctrine of the 1870s and 1880s, devised the tactic of placing torpedo boats alongside battleships; these would hide behind the larger ships until gun-smoke obscured visibility enough for them to dart out and fire their torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] While this tactic was made less effective by the development of smokeless propellant, the threat from more capable torpedo craft (later including submarines) remained.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, the Royal Navy had developed the first destroyers, which were initially designed to intercept and drive off any attacking torpedo boats.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The other major naval powers quickly followed suit with similar vessels of their own.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The presence of battleships had a great psychological and diplomatic impact.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Similar to possessing nuclear weapons in the second half of the 20th century, the ownership of battleships marked a country as a regional or global power, and the ability to build them domestically signified that a country could claim to be a great power.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Even during the Cold War, the psychological impact of a battleship was significant.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] In September 1983, when Druze militia in Lebanon's Shouf Mountains fired upon U.S.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Marine peacekeepers, the arrival of USS *New Jersey* stopped the firing.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Gunfire from *New Jersey* later killed militia leaders.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] Battleships were the largest and most complex, and hence the most expensive warships of their time; as a result, the value of investment in battleships has always been contested.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] As the French politician Etienne Lamy wrote in 1879, "The construction of battleships is so costly, their effectiveness so uncertain and of such short duration, that the enterprise of creating an armored fleet seems to leave fruitless the perseverance of a people".
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The *Jeune École* school of thought of the 1870s and 1880s sought alternatives to the crippling expense and debatable utility of a conventional battlefleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] It proposed what would nowadays be termed a sea denial strategy, based on fast, long-ranged cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo boat flotillas to attack enemy ships attempting to blockade French ports.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The ideas of the *Jeune École* were ahead of their time; it was not until the 20th century that efficient mines, torpedoes, submarines, and aircraft were available that allowed similar ideas to be effectively implemented.
[src:french-ship-gloire/battleship-p02] The determination of powers such as Germany to build battlefleets with which to confront much stronger rivals has been criticized by historians, who emphasize the futility of investment in a battlefleet that has no chance of matching its opponent in an actual battle.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Modern cruisers are generally the largest ships in a fleet after aircraft carriers and amphibious assault ships, and can usually perform several operational roles from search-and-destroy to ocean escort to sea denial.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The term "cruiser", which has been in use for several hundred years, has changed its meaning over time.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] During the Age of Sail, the term *cruising* referred to certain kinds of missions—independent scouting, commerce protection, or raiding—usually fulfilled by frigates or sloops-of-war, which functioned as the *cruising warships* of a fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In the middle of the 19th century, *cruiser* came to be a classification of the ships intended for cruising distant waters, for commerce raiding, and for scouting for the battle fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Cruisers came in a wide variety of sizes, from the medium-sized protected cruiser to large armored cruisers that were nearly as big (although not as powerful or as well-armored) as a pre-dreadnought battleship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] With the advent of the dreadnought battleship before World War I, the armored cruiser evolved into a vessel of similar scale known as the battlecruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The very large battlecruisers of the World War I era that succeeded armored cruisers were now classified, along with dreadnought battleships, as capital ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] After World War II, the advent of guided missiles allowed cruisers to replace the battleship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The term "cruiser" or "cruizer" was first commonly used in the 17th century to refer to an independent warship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] "Cruiser" meant the purpose or mission of a ship, rather than a category of vessel.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] However, the term was nonetheless used to mean a smaller, faster warship suitable for such a role.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In the 17th century, the ship of the line was generally too large, inflexible, and expensive to be dispatched on long-range missions (for instance, to the Americas), and too strategically important to be put at risk of fouling and foundering by continual patrol duties.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Dutch navy was noted for its cruisers in the 17th century, while the Royal Navy—and later French and Spanish navies—subsequently caught up in terms of their numbers and deployment.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The British Cruiser and Convoy Acts were an attempt by mercantile interests in Parliament to focus the Navy on commerce defence and raiding with cruisers, rather than the more scarce and expensive ships of the line.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] During the 18th century the frigate became the preeminent type of cruiser.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] A frigate was a small, fast, long range, lightly armed (single gun-deck) ship used for scouting, carrying dispatches, and disrupting enemy trade.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The other principal type of cruiser was the sloop, but many other miscellaneous types of ship were used as well.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] During the 19th century, navies began to use steam power for their fleets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The 1840s saw the construction of experimental steam-powered frigates and sloops.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] By the middle of the 1850s, the British and U.S.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Navies were both building steam frigates with very long hulls and a heavy gun armament, for instance USS *Merrimack* or *Mersey*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The 1860s saw the introduction of the ironclad.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The first ironclads were frigates, in the sense of having one gun deck; however, they were also clearly the most powerful ships in the navy, and were principally to serve in the line of battle.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In spite of their great speed, they would have been wasted in a cruising role.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The French constructed a number of smaller ironclads for overseas cruising duties, starting with the *Belliqueuse*, commissioned 1865.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] These "station ironclads" were the beginning of the development of the armored cruisers, a type of ironclad specifically for the traditional cruiser missions of fast, independent raiding and patrol.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The first true armored cruiser was the Russian *General-Admiral*, completed in 1874, and followed by the British *Shannon* a few years later.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Until the 1890s armored cruisers were still built with masts for a full sailing rig, to enable them to operate far from friendly coaling stations.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Unarmored cruising warships, built out of wood, iron, steel or a combination of those materials, remained popular until towards the end of the 19th century.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The ironclad's armor often meant that they were limited to short range under steam, and many ironclads were unsuited to long-range missions or for work in distant colonies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The unarmored cruiser—often a screw sloop or screw frigate—could continue in this role.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Even though mid- to late-19th century cruisers typically carried up-to-date guns firing explosive shells, they were unable to face ironclads in combat.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] This was evidenced by the clash between HMS *Shah*, a modern British cruiser, and the Peruvian monitor *Huáscar*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Even though the Peruvian vessel was obsolete by the time of the encounter, it stood up well to roughly 50 hits from British shells.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In the 1880s, naval engineers began to use steel as a material for construction and armament.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] A steel cruiser could be lighter and faster than one built of iron or wood.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The *Jeune Ecole* school of naval doctrine suggested that a fleet of fast unprotected steel cruisers were ideal for commerce raiding, while the torpedo boat would be able to destroy an enemy battleship fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Steel also offered the cruiser a way of acquiring the protection needed to survive in combat.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Steel armor was considerably stronger, for the same weight, than iron.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] By putting a relatively thin layer of steel armor above the vital parts of the ship, and by placing the coal bunkers where they might stop shellfire, a useful degree of protection could be achieved without slowing the ship too much.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Protected cruisers generally had an armored deck with sloped sides, providing similar protection to a light armored belt at less weight and expense.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The first protected cruiser was the Chilean ship *Esmeralda*, launched in 1883.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Produced by a shipyard at Elswick, in Britain, owned by Armstrong, she inspired a group of protected cruisers produced in the same yard and known as the "Elswick cruisers".
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Her forecastle, poop deck and the wooden board deck had been removed, replaced with an armored deck.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The torpedo cruiser (known in the Royal Navy as the torpedo gunboat) was a smaller unarmored cruiser, which emerged in the 1880s–1890s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] These ships could reach speeds up to 20 knots (37 km/h) and were armed with medium to small calibre guns as well as torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] These ships were tasked with guard and reconnaissance duties, to repeat signals and all other fleet duties for which smaller vessels were suited.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] These ships could also function as flagships of torpedo boat flotillas.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] After the 1900s, these ships were usually traded for faster ships with better sea going qualities.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Steel also affected the construction and role of armored cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Steel meant that new designs of battleship, later known as pre-dreadnought battleships, would be able to combine firepower and armor with better endurance and speed than ever before.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Because of their similarity, the lines between battleships and armored cruisers became blurred.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Shortly after the turn of the 20th century there were difficult questions about the design of future cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Modern armored cruisers, almost as powerful as battleships, were also fast enough to outrun older protected and unarmored cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In the Royal Navy, Jackie Fisher cut back hugely on older vessels, including many cruisers of different sorts, calling them "a miser's hoard of useless junk" that any modern cruiser would sweep from the seas.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The scout cruiser also appeared in this era; this was a small, fast, lightly armed and armored type designed primarily for reconnaissance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Royal Navy and the Italian Navy were the primary developers of this type.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The growing size and power of the armored cruiser resulted in the battlecruiser, with an armament and size similar to the revolutionary new dreadnought battleship; the brainchild of British admiral Jackie Fisher.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] He believed that to ensure British naval dominance in its overseas colonial possessions, a fleet of large, fast, powerfully armed vessels which would be able to hunt down and mop up enemy cruisers and armored cruisers with overwhelming fire superiority was needed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] They were equipped with the same gun types as battleships, though usually with fewer guns, and were intended to engage enemy capital ships as well.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] This type of vessel came to be known as the *battlecruiser*, and the first were commissioned into the Royal Navy in 1907.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The British battlecruisers sacrificed protection for speed, as they were intended to "choose their range" (to the enemy) with superior speed and only engage the enemy at long range.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] When engaged at moderate ranges, the lack of protection combined with unsafe ammunition handling practices became tragic with the loss of three of them at the Battle of Jutland.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Germany and eventually Japan followed suit to build these vessels, replacing armored cruisers in most frontline roles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] German battlecruisers were generally better protected but slower than British battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Battlecruisers were in many cases larger and more expensive than contemporary battleships, due to their much larger propulsion plants.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] At around the same time as the battlecruiser was developed, the distinction between the armored and the unarmored cruiser finally disappeared.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] By the British Town class, the first of which was launched in 1909, it was possible for a small, fast cruiser to carry both belt and deck armor, particularly when turbine engines were adopted.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] These light armored cruisers began to occupy the traditional cruiser role once it became clear that the battlecruiser squadrons were required to operate with the battle fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Some light cruisers were built specifically to act as the leaders of flotillas of destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] These vessels were essentially large coastal patrol boats armed with multiple light guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] One such warship was *Grivița* of the Romanian Navy.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] She displaced 110 tons, measured 60 meters in length and was armed with four light guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The auxiliary cruiser was a merchant ship hastily armed with small guns on the outbreak of war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Auxiliary cruisers were used to fill gaps in their long-range lines or provide escort for other cargo ships, although they generally proved to be useless in this role because of their low speed, feeble firepower and lack of armor.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In both world wars the Germans also used small merchant ships armed with cruiser guns to surprise Allied merchant ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Some large liners were armed in the same way.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In British service these were known as Armed Merchant Cruisers (AMC).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Germans and French used them in World War I as raiders because of their high speed (around 30 knots (56 km/h)), and they were used again as raiders early in World War II by the Germans and Japanese.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In both the First World War and in the early part of the Second, they were used as convoy escorts by the British.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Cruisers were one of the workhorse types of warship during World War I.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] By the time of World War I, cruisers had accelerated their development and improved their quality significantly, with drainage volume reaching 3000–4000 tons, a speed of 25–30 knots and a calibre of 127–152 mm.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Naval construction in the 1920s and 1930s was limited by international treaties designed to prevent the repetition of the Dreadnought arms race of the early 20th century.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Washington Naval Treaty of 1922 placed limits on the construction of ships with a standard displacement of more than 10,000 tons and an armament of guns larger than 8-inch (203 mm).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] A number of navies commissioned classes of cruisers at the top end of this limit, known as "treaty cruisers".
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The London Naval Treaty in 1930 then formalised the distinction between these "heavy" cruisers and light cruisers: a "heavy" cruiser was one with guns of more than 6.1-inch (155 mm) calibre.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Second London Naval Treaty attempted to reduce the tonnage of new cruisers to 8,000 or less, but this had little effect; Japan and Germany were not signatories, and some navies had already begun to evade treaty limitations on warships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The first London treaty did touch off a period of the major powers building 6-inch or 6.1-inch gunned cruisers, nominally of 10,000 tons and with up to fifteen guns, the treaty limit.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Thus, most light cruisers ordered after 1930 were the size of heavy cruisers but with more and smaller guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Imperial Japanese Navy began this new race with the *Mogami* class, launched in 1934.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] After building smaller light cruisers with six or eight 6-inch guns launched 1931–35, the British Royal Navy followed with the 12-gun *Southampton* class in 1936.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The heavy cruiser was a type of cruiser designed for long range, high speed and an armament of naval guns around 203 mm (8 in) in calibre.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The first heavy cruisers were built in 1915, although it only became a widespread classification following the London Naval Treaty in 1930.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The heavy cruiser's immediate precursors were the light cruiser designs of the 1910s and 1920s; the US lightly armored 8-inch "treaty cruisers" of the 1920s (built under the Washington Naval Treaty) were originally classed as light cruisers until the London Treaty forced their redesignation.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Initially, all cruisers built under the Washington treaty had torpedo tubes, regardless of nationality.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] However, in 1930, results of war games caused the US Naval War College to conclude that only perhaps half of cruisers would use their torpedoes in action.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In a surface engagement, long-range gunfire and destroyer torpedoes would decide the issue, and under air attack numerous cruisers would be lost before getting within torpedo range.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Thus, beginning with USS *New Orleans* launched in 1933, new cruisers were built without torpedoes, and torpedoes were removed from older heavy cruisers due to the perceived hazard of their being exploded by shell fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Japanese took exactly the opposite approach with cruiser torpedoes, and this proved crucial to their tactical victories in most of the numerous cruiser actions of 1942.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Beginning with the *Furutaka* class launched in 1925, every Japanese heavy cruiser was armed with 24-inch (610 mm) torpedoes, larger than any other cruisers'.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] By 1933 Japan had developed the Type 93 torpedo for these ships, eventually nicknamed "Long Lance" by the Allies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] This type used compressed oxygen instead of compressed air, allowing it to achieve ranges and speeds unmatched by other torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] It could achieve a range of 22,000 metres (24,000 yd) at 50 knots (93 km/h; 58 mph), compared with the US Mark 15 torpedo with 5,500 metres (6,000 yd) at 45 knots (83 km/h; 52 mph).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Mark 15 had a maximum range of 13,500 metres (14,800 yd) at 26.5 knots (49.1 km/h; 30.5 mph), still well below the "Long Lance".
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Japanese were able to keep the Type 93's performance and oxygen power secret until the Allies recovered one in early 1943, thus the Allies faced a great threat they were not aware of in 1942.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The Type 93 was also fitted to Japanese post-1930 light cruisers and the majority of their World War II destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Heavy cruisers continued in use until after World War II, with some converted to guided-missile cruisers for air defense or strategic attack and some used for shore bombardment by the United States in the Korean War and the Vietnam War.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The German *Deutschland* class was a series of three *Panzerschiffe* ("armored ships"), a form of heavily armed cruiser, designed and built by the German Reichsmarine in nominal accordance with restrictions imposed by the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] All three ships were launched between 1931 and 1934, and served with Germany's Kriegsmarine during World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Within the Kriegsmarine, the Panzerschiffe had the propaganda value of capital ships: heavy cruisers with battleship guns, torpedoes, and scout aircraft.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] (The similar Swedish *Panzerschiffe* were tactically used as centers of battlefleets and not as cruisers.) They were deployed by Nazi Germany in support of the German interests in the Spanish Civil War.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Panzerschiff *Admiral Graf Spee* represented Germany in the 1937 Coronation Fleet Review.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The British press referred to the vessels as pocket battleships, in reference to the heavy firepower contained in the relatively small vessels; they were considerably smaller than contemporary battleships, though at 28 knots were slower than battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] At up to 16,000 tons at full load, they were not treaty compliant 10,000 ton cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] And although their displacement and scale of armor protection were that of a heavy cruiser, their 280 mm (11 in) main armament was heavier than the 203 mm (8 in) guns of other nations' heavy cruisers, and the latter two members of the class also had tall conning towers resembling battleships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] They were seen in the 1930s as a new and serious threat by both Britain and France.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] While the Kriegsmarine reclassified them as heavy cruisers in 1940, *Deutschland*-class ships continued to be called *pocket battleships* in the popular press.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The American *Alaska* class represented the supersized cruiser design.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Due to the German pocket battleships, the *Scharnhorst* class, and rumored Japanese "super cruisers", all of which carried guns larger than the standard heavy cruiser's 8-inch size dictated by naval treaty limitations, the *Alaska*s were intended to be "cruiser-killers".
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] While superficially appearing similar to a battleship/battlecruiser and mounting three triple turrets of 12-inch guns, their actual protection scheme and design resembled a scaled-up heavy cruiser design.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Their hull classification symbol of CB (cruiser, big) reflected this.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] A precursor to the anti-aircraft cruiser was the Romanian British-built protected cruiser *Elisabeta*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] After the start of World War I, her four 120 mm main guns were landed and her four 75 mm (12-pounder) secondary guns were modified for anti-aircraft fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The development of the anti-aircraft cruiser began in 1935 when the Royal Navy re-armed HMS *Coventry* and HMS *Curlew*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Torpedo tubes and 6-inch (152 mm) low-angle guns were removed from these World War I light cruisers and replaced with ten 4-inch (102 mm) high-angle guns, with appropriate fire-control equipment to provide larger warships with protection against high-altitude bombers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] A tactical shortcoming was recognised after completing six additional conversions of C-class cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Having sacrificed anti-ship weapons for anti-aircraft armament, the converted anti-aircraft cruisers might themselves need protection against surface units.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] New construction was undertaken to create cruisers of similar speed and displacement with dual-purpose guns, which offered good anti-aircraft protection with anti-surface capability for the traditional light cruiser role of defending capital ships from destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The first purpose built anti-aircraft cruiser was the British *Dido* class, completed in 1940–42.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] The US Navy's *Atlanta*-class cruisers (CLAA: light cruiser with anti-aircraft capability) were designed to match the capabilities of the Royal Navy.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Both *Dido* and *Atlanta* cruisers initially carried torpedo tubes; the *Atlanta* cruisers at least were originally designed as destroyer leaders, were originally designated CL (light cruiser), and did not receive the CLAA designation until 1949.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Most post-World War II cruisers were tasked with air defense roles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] In the early 1950s, advances in aviation technology forced the move from anti-aircraft artillery to anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Therefore, most modern cruisers are equipped with surface-to-air missiles as their main armament.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p01] Today's equivalent of the anti-aircraft cruiser is the **guided-missile cruiser** (CAG/CLG/CG/CGN).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Cruisers participated in a number of surface engagements in the early part of World War II, along with escorting carrier and battleship groups throughout the war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In the later part of the war, Allied cruisers primarily provided anti-aircraft (AA) escort for carrier groups and performed shore bombardment.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Japanese cruisers similarly escorted carrier and battleship groups in the later part of the war, notably in the disastrous Battle of the Philippine Sea and Battle of Leyte Gulf.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In 1937–41 the Japanese, having withdrawn from all naval treaties, upgraded or completed the *Mogami* and *Tone* classes as heavy cruisers by replacing their 6.1 in (155 mm) triple turrets with 8 in (203 mm) twin turrets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Torpedo refits were also made to most heavy cruisers, resulting in up to sixteen 24 in (610 mm) tubes per ship, plus a set of reloads.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In 1941 the 1920s light cruisers *Ōi* and *Kitakami* were converted to torpedo cruisers with four 5.5 in (140 mm) guns and forty 24 in (610 mm) torpedo tubes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In 1944 *Kitakami* was further converted to carry up to eight *Kaiten* human torpedoes in place of ordinary torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Before World War II, cruisers were mainly divided into three types: heavy cruisers, light cruisers and auxiliary cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Heavy cruiser tonnage reached 20–30,000 tons, speed 32–34 knots, endurance of more than 10,000 nautical miles, armor thickness of 127–203 mm.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Heavy cruisers were equipped with eight or nine 8 in (203 mm) guns with a range of more than 20 nautical miles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] They were mainly used to attack enemy surface ships and shore-based targets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In addition, there were 10–16 secondary guns with a caliber of less than 130 mm (5.1 in).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Also, dozens of automatic antiaircraft guns were installed to fight aircraft and small vessels such as torpedo boats.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] For example, in World War II, American Alaska-class cruisers were more than 30,000 tons, equipped with nine 12 in (305 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Some cruisers could also carry three or four seaplanes to correct the accuracy of gunfire and perform reconnaissance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Together with battleships, these heavy cruisers formed powerful naval task forces, which dominated the world's oceans for more than a century.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] After the signing of the Washington Treaty on Arms Limitation in 1922, the tonnage and quantity of battleships, aircraft carriers and cruisers were severely restricted.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In order not to violate the treaty, countries began to develop light cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Light cruisers of the 1920s had displacements of less than 10,000 tons and a speed of up to 35 knots.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] They were equipped with 6–12 main guns with a caliber of 127–133 mm (5–5.5 inches).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In addition, they were equipped with 8–12 secondary guns under 127 mm (5 in) and dozens of small caliber cannons, as well as torpedoes and mines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Some ships also carried 2–4 seaplanes, mainly for reconnaissance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In 1930 the London Naval Treaty allowed large light cruisers to be built, with the same tonnage as heavy cruisers and armed with up to fifteen 155 mm (6.1 in) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese *Mogami* class were built to this treaty's limit, the Americans and British also built similar ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] However, in 1939 the *Mogami*s were refitted as heavy cruisers with ten 203 mm (8.0 in) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In December 1939, three British cruisers engaged the German "pocket battleship" *Admiral Graf Spee* (which was on a commerce raiding mission) in the Battle of the River Plate; German cruiser Admiral Graf Spee then took refuge in neutral Montevideo, Uruguay.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] By broadcasting messages indicating capital ships were in the area, the British caused *Admiral Graf Spee*'s captain to think he faced a hopeless situation while low on ammunition and order his ship scuttled.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 8 June 1940 the German capital ships *Scharnhorst* and *Gneisenau*, classed as battleships but with large cruiser armament, sank the aircraft carrier HMS *Glorious* with gunfire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] From October 1940 through March 1941 the German heavy cruiser (also known as "pocket battleship", see above) *Admiral Scheer* conducted a successful commerce-raiding voyage in the Atlantic and Indian Oceans.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 27 May 1941, HMS *Dorsetshire* attempted to finish off the German battleship *Bismarck* with torpedoes, probably causing the Germans to scuttle the ship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] *Bismarck* (accompanied by the heavy cruiser *Prinz Eugen*) previously sank the battlecruiser HMS *Hood* and damaged the battleship HMS *Prince of Wales* with gunfire in the Battle of the Denmark Strait.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 19 November 1941, HMAS *Sydney* sank in a mutually fatal engagement with the German raider *Kormoran* in the Indian Ocean near Western Australia.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Twenty-three British cruisers were lost to enemy action, mostly to air attack and submarines, in operations in the Atlantic, Mediterranean, and Indian Ocean.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Sixteen of these losses were in the Mediterranean.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The British included cruisers and anti-aircraft cruisers among convoy escorts in the Mediterranean and to northern Russia due to the threat of surface and air attack.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Almost all cruisers in World War II were vulnerable to submarine attack due to a lack of anti-submarine sonar and weapons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Also, until 1943–44 the light anti-aircraft armament of most cruisers was weak.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In July 1942 an attempt to intercept Convoy PQ 17 with surface ships, including the heavy cruiser *Admiral Scheer*, failed due to multiple German warships grounding, but air and submarine attacks sank 2/3 of the convoy's ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In August 1942 *Admiral Scheer* conducted Operation Wunderland, a solo raid into northern Russia's Kara Sea.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] She bombarded Dikson Island but otherwise had little success.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 31 December 1942 the Battle of the Barents Sea was fought, a rare action for a Murmansk run because it involved cruisers on both sides.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Four British destroyers and five other vessels were escorting Convoy JW 51B from the UK to the Murmansk area.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Another British force of two cruisers (HMS *Sheffield* and HMS *Jamaica*) and two destroyers were in the area.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Two heavy cruisers (one the "pocket battleship" *Lützow*), accompanied by six destroyers, attempted to intercept the convoy near North Cape after it was spotted by a U-boat.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Although the Germans sank a British destroyer and a minesweeper (also damaging another destroyer), they failed to damage any of the convoy's merchant ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] A German destroyer was lost and a heavy cruiser damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Both sides withdrew from the action for fear of the other side's torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 26 December 1943, the German capital ship *Scharnhorst* was sunk while attempting to intercept a convoy in the Battle of the North Cape.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The British force that sank her was led by Vice Admiral Bruce Fraser in the battleship HMS *Duke of York*, accompanied by four cruisers and nine destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] One of the cruisers was the preserved HMS *Belfast*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The attack on Pearl Harbor on 7 December 1941 brought the United States into the war, but with eight battleships sunk or damaged by air attack.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 10 December 1941 HMS *Prince of Wales* and the battlecruiser HMS *Repulse* were sunk by land-based torpedo bombers northeast of Singapore.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] It was now clear that surface ships could not operate near enemy aircraft in daylight without air cover; most surface actions of 1942–43 were fought at night as a result.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Generally, both sides avoided risking their battleships until the Japanese attack at Leyte Gulf in 1944.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Six of the battleships from Pearl Harbor were eventually returned to service, but no US battleships engaged Japanese surface units at sea until the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November 1942, and not thereafter until the Battle of Surigao Strait in October 1944.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] USS *North Carolina* was on hand for the initial landings at Guadalcanal on 7 August 1942, and escorted carriers in the Battle of the Eastern Solomons later that month.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] However, on 15 September she was torpedoed while escorting a carrier group and had to return to the US for repairs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Generally, the Japanese held their capital ships out of all surface actions in the 1941–42 campaigns or they failed to close with the enemy; the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November 1942 was the sole exception.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The four *Kongō*-class ships performed shore bombardment in Malaya, Singapore, and Guadalcanal and escorted the raid on Ceylon and other carrier forces in 1941–42.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Japanese capital ships also participated ineffectively (due to not being engaged) in the Battle of Midway and the simultaneous Aleutian diversion; in both cases they were in battleship groups well to the rear of the carrier groups.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Sources state that *Yamato* sat out the entire Guadalcanal campaign due to lack of high-explosive bombardment shells, poor nautical charts of the area, and high fuel consumption.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] It is likely that the poor charts affected other battleships as well.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Except for the *Kongō* class, most Japanese battleships spent the critical year of 1942, in which most of the war's surface actions occurred, in home waters or at the fortified base of Truk, far from any risk of attacking or being attacked.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Destroyers also participated heavily on both sides of these battles and provided essentially all the torpedoes on the Allied side, with some battles in these campaigns fought entirely between destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Along with lack of knowledge of the capabilities of the Long Lance torpedo, the US Navy was hampered by a deficiency it was initially unaware of—the unreliability of the Mark 15 torpedo used by destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] This weapon shared the Mark 6 exploder and other problems with the more famously unreliable Mark 14 torpedo; the most common results of firing either of these torpedoes were a dud or a miss.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The problems with these weapons were not solved until mid-1943, after almost all of the surface actions in the Solomon Islands had taken place.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Another factor that shaped the early surface actions was the pre-war training of both sides.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US Navy concentrated on long-range 8-inch gunfire as their primary offensive weapon, leading to rigid battle line tactics, while the Japanese trained extensively for nighttime torpedo attacks.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Since all post-1930 Japanese cruisers had 8-inch guns by 1941, almost all of the US Navy's cruisers in the South Pacific in 1942 were the 8-inch-gunned (203 mm) "treaty cruisers"; most of the 6-inch-gunned (152 mm) cruisers were deployed in the Atlantic.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Although their battleships were held out of surface action, Japanese cruiser-destroyer forces rapidly isolated and mopped up the Allied naval forces in the Dutch East Indies campaign of February–March 1942.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In three separate actions, they sank five Allied cruisers (two Dutch and one each British, Australian, and American) with torpedoes and gunfire, against one Japanese cruiser damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] With one other Allied cruiser withdrawn for repairs, the only remaining Allied cruiser in the area was the damaged USS *Marblehead*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Despite their rapid success, the Japanese proceeded methodically, never leaving their air cover and rapidly establishing new air bases as they advanced.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] After the key carrier battles of the Coral Sea and Midway in mid-1942, Japan had lost four of the six fleet carriers that launched the Pearl Harbor raid and was on the strategic defensive.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 7 August 1942 US Marines were landed on Guadalcanal and other nearby islands, beginning the Guadalcanal campaign.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] This campaign proved to be a severe test for the Navy as well as the Marines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Along with two carrier battles, several major surface actions occurred, almost all at night between cruiser-destroyer forces.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On the night of 8–9 August 1942 the Japanese counterattacked near Guadalcanal in the Battle of Savo Island with a cruiser-destroyer force.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In a controversial move, the US carrier task forces were withdrawn from the area on the 8th due to heavy fighter losses and low fuel.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Allied force included six heavy cruisers (two Australian), two light cruisers (one Australian), and eight US destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Of the cruisers, only the Australian ships had torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese force included five heavy cruisers, two light cruisers, and one destroyer.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Numerous circumstances combined to reduce Allied readiness for the battle.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The results of the battle were three American heavy cruisers sunk by torpedoes and gunfire, one Australian heavy cruiser disabled by gunfire and scuttled, one heavy cruiser damaged, and two US destroyers damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese had three cruisers lightly damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] This was the most lopsided outcome of the surface actions in the Solomon Islands.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Along with their superior torpedoes, the opening Japanese gunfire was accurate and very damaging.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Subsequent analysis showed that some of the damage was due to poor housekeeping practices by US forces.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Stowage of boats and aircraft in midships hangars with full gas tanks contributed to fires, along with full and unprotected ready-service ammunition lockers for the open-mount secondary armament.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] These practices were soon corrected, and US cruisers with similar damage sank less often thereafter.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Savo was the first surface action of the war for almost all the US ships and personnel; few US cruisers and destroyers were targeted or hit at Coral Sea or Midway.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 24–25 August 1942 the Battle of the Eastern Solomons, a major carrier action, was fought.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Part of the action was a Japanese attempt to reinforce Guadalcanal with men and equipment on troop transports.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese troop convoy was attacked by Allied aircraft, resulting in the Japanese subsequently reinforcing Guadalcanal with troops on fast warships at night.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] These convoys were called the "Tokyo Express" by the Allies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Although the Tokyo Express often ran unopposed, most surface actions in the Solomons revolved around Tokyo Express missions.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Also, US air operations had commenced from Henderson Field, the airfield on Guadalcanal.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Fear of air power on both sides resulted in all surface actions in the Solomons being fought at night.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Battle of Cape Esperance occurred on the night of 11–12 October 1942.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] A Tokyo Express mission was underway for Guadalcanal at the same time as a separate cruiser-destroyer bombardment group loaded with high explosive shells for bombarding Henderson Field.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] A US cruiser-destroyer force was deployed in advance of a convoy of US Army troops for Guadalcanal that was due on 13 October.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Tokyo Express convoy was two seaplane tenders and six destroyers; the bombardment group was three heavy cruisers and two destroyers, and the US force was two heavy cruisers, two light cruisers, and five destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US force engaged the Japanese bombardment force; the Tokyo Express convoy was able to unload on Guadalcanal and evade action.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The bombardment force was sighted at close range (5,000 yards (4,600 m)) and the US force opened fire.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese were surprised because their admiral was anticipating sighting the Tokyo Express force, and withheld fire while attempting to confirm the US ships' identity.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] One Japanese cruiser and one destroyer were sunk and one cruiser damaged, against one US destroyer sunk with one light cruiser and one destroyer damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The bombardment force failed to bring its torpedoes into action, and turned back.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The next day US aircraft from Henderson Field attacked several of the Japanese ships, sinking two destroyers and damaging a third.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US victory resulted in overconfidence in some later battles, reflected in the initial after-action report claiming two Japanese heavy cruisers, one light cruiser, and three destroyers sunk by the gunfire of *Boise* alone.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The battle had little effect on the overall situation, as the next night two Kongō-class battleships bombarded and severely damaged Henderson Field unopposed, and the following night another Tokyo Express convoy delivered 4,500 troops to Guadalcanal.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US convoy delivered the Army troops as scheduled on the 13th.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands took place 25–27 October 1942.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] It was a pivotal battle, as it left the US and Japanese with only two large carriers each in the South Pacific (another large Japanese carrier was damaged and under repair until May 1943).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Due to the high carrier attrition rate with no replacements for months, for the most part both sides stopped risking their remaining carriers until late 1943, and each side sent in a pair of battleships instead.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The next major carrier operations for the US were the carrier raid on Rabaul and support for the invasion of Tarawa, both in November 1943.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Naval Battle of Guadalcanal occurred 12–15 November 1942 in two phases.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] A night surface action on 12–13 November was the first phase.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese force consisted of two Kongō-class battleships with high explosive shells for bombarding Henderson Field, one small light cruiser, and 11 destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Their plan was that the bombardment would neutralize Allied airpower and allow a force of 11 transport ships and 12 destroyers to reinforce Guadalcanal with a Japanese division the next day.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] However, US reconnaissance aircraft spotted the approaching Japanese on the 12th and the Americans made what preparations they could.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The American force consisted of two heavy cruisers, one light cruiser, two anti-aircraft cruisers, and eight destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Americans were outgunned by the Japanese that night, and a lack of pre-battle orders by the US commander led to confusion.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The destroyer USS *Laffey* closed with the battleship *Hiei*, firing all torpedoes (though apparently none hit or detonated) and raking the battleship's bridge with gunfire, wounding the Japanese admiral and killing his chief of staff.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Americans initially lost four destroyers including *Laffey*, with both heavy cruisers, most of the remaining destroyers, and both anti-aircraft cruisers damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese initially had one battleship and four destroyers damaged, but at this point they withdrew, possibly unaware that the US force was unable to further oppose them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] At dawn US aircraft from Henderson Field, USS *Enterprise*, and Espiritu Santo found the damaged battleship and two destroyers in the area.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The battleship (*Hiei*) was sunk by aircraft (or possibly scuttled), one destroyer was sunk by the damaged USS *Portland*, and the other destroyer was attacked by aircraft but was able to withdraw.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Both of the damaged US anti-aircraft cruisers were lost on 13 November, one (*Juneau*) torpedoed by a Japanese submarine, and the other sank on the way to repairs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] *Juneau*'s loss was especially tragic; the submarine's presence prevented immediate rescue, over 100 survivors of a crew of nearly 700 were adrift for eight days, and all but ten died.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Among the dead were the five Sullivan brothers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese transport force was rescheduled for the 14th and a new cruiser-destroyer force (belatedly joined by the surviving battleship *Kirishima*) was sent to bombard Henderson Field the night of 13 November.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Only two cruisers actually bombarded the airfield, as *Kirishima* had not arrived yet and the remainder of the force was on guard for US warships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The cruiser-destroyer force then withdrew, while the transport force continued towards Guadalcanal.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Both forces were attacked by US aircraft on the 14th.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The cruiser force lost one heavy cruiser sunk and one damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Although the transport force had fighter cover from the carrier *Jun'yō*, six transports were sunk and one heavily damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] All but four of the destroyers accompanying the transport force picked up survivors and withdrew.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The remaining four transports and four destroyers approached Guadalcanal at night, but stopped to await the results of the night's action.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On the night of 14–15 November a Japanese force of *Kirishima*, two heavy and two light cruisers, and nine destroyers approached Guadalcanal.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Two US battleships (*Washington* and *South Dakota*) were there to meet them, along with four destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] This was one of only two battleship-on-battleship encounters during the Pacific War; the other was the lopsided Battle of Surigao Strait in October 1944, part of the Battle of Leyte Gulf.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The battleships had been escorting *Enterprise*, but were detached due to the urgency of the situation.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] With nine 16-inch (406 mm) guns apiece against eight 14-inch (356 mm) guns on *Kirishima*, the Americans had major gun and armor advantages.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] All four destroyers were sunk or severely damaged and withdrawn shortly after the Japanese attacked them with gunfire and torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Although her main battery remained in action for most of the battle, *South Dakota* spent much of the action dealing with major electrical failures that affected her radar, fire control, and radio systems.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Although her armor was not penetrated, she was hit by 26 shells of various calibers and temporarily rendered, in a US admiral's words, "deaf, dumb, blind, and impotent".
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] *Washington* went undetected by the Japanese for most of the battle, but withheld shooting to avoid "friendly fire" until *South Dakota* was illuminated by Japanese fire, then rapidly set *Kirishima* ablaze with a jammed rudder and other damage.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] *Washington*, finally spotted by the Japanese, then headed for the Russell Islands to hopefully draw the Japanese away from Guadalcanal and *South Dakota*, and was successful in evading several torpedo attacks.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Unusually, only a few Japanese torpedoes scored hits in this engagement.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] *Kirishima* sank or was scuttled before the night was out, along with two Japanese destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The remaining Japanese ships withdrew, except for the four transports, which beached themselves in the night and started unloading.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] However, dawn (and US aircraft, US artillery, and a US destroyer) found them still beached, and they were destroyed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Battle of Tassafaronga took place on the night of 30 November – 1 December 1942.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US had four heavy cruisers, one light cruiser, and four destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese had eight destroyers on a Tokyo Express run to deliver food and supplies in drums to Guadalcanal.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Americans achieved initial surprise, damaging one destroyer with gunfire which later sank, but the Japanese torpedo counterattack was devastating.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] One American heavy cruiser was sunk and three others heavily damaged, with the bows blown off of two of them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] It was significant that these two were not lost to Long Lance hits as happened in previous battles; American battle readiness and damage control had improved.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Despite defeating the Americans, the Japanese withdrew without delivering the crucial supplies to Guadalcanal.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Another attempt on 3 December dropped 1,500 drums of supplies near Guadalcanal, but Allied strafing aircraft sank all but 300 before the Japanese Army could recover them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On 7 December PT boats interrupted a Tokyo Express run, and the following night sank a Japanese supply submarine.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The next day the Japanese Navy proposed stopping all destroyer runs to Guadalcanal, but agreed to do just one more.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] This was on 11 December and was also intercepted by PT boats, which sank a destroyer; only 200 of 1,200 drums dropped off the island were recovered.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The next day the Japanese Navy proposed abandoning Guadalcanal; this was approved by the Imperial General Headquarters on 31 December and the Japanese left the island in early February 1943.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] After the Japanese abandoned Guadalcanal in February 1943, Allied operations in the Pacific shifted to the New Guinea campaign and isolating Rabaul.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Battle of Kula Gulf was fought on the night of 5–6 July.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US had three light cruisers and four destroyers; the Japanese had ten destroyers loaded with 2,600 troops destined for Vila to oppose a recent US landing on Rendova.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Although the Japanese sank a cruiser, they lost two destroyers and were able to deliver only 850 troops.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] On the night of 12–13 July, the Battle of Kolombangara occurred.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Allies had three light cruisers (one New Zealand) and ten destroyers; the Japanese had one small light cruiser and five destroyers, a Tokyo Express run for Vila.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] All three Allied cruisers were heavily damaged, with the New Zealand cruiser put out of action for 25 months by a Long Lance hit.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Allies sank only the Japanese light cruiser, and the Japanese landed 1,200 troops at Vila.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Despite their tactical victory, this battle caused the Japanese to use a different route in the future, where they were more vulnerable to destroyer and PT boat attacks.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Battle of Empress Augusta Bay was fought on the night of 1–2 November 1943, immediately after US Marines invaded Bougainville in the Solomon Islands.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] A Japanese heavy cruiser was damaged by a nighttime air attack shortly before the battle; it is likely that Allied airborne radar had progressed far enough to allow night operations.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Americans had four of the new *Cleveland*-class cruisers and eight destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese had two heavy cruisers, two small light cruisers, and six destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Both sides were plagued by collisions, shells that failed to explode, and mutual skill in dodging torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Americans suffered significant damage to three destroyers and light damage to a cruiser, but no losses.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese lost one light cruiser and a destroyer, with four other ships damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese withdrew; the Americans pursued them until dawn, then returned to the landing area to provide anti-aircraft cover.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] After the Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands in October 1942, both sides were short of large aircraft carriers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US suspended major carrier operations until sufficient carriers could be completed to destroy the entire Japanese fleet at once should it appear.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Central Pacific carrier raids and amphibious operations commenced in November 1943 with a carrier raid on Rabaul (preceded and followed by Fifth Air Force attacks) and the bloody but successful invasion of Tarawa.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The air attacks on Rabaul crippled the Japanese cruiser force, with four heavy and two light cruisers damaged; they were withdrawn to Truk.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US had built up a force in the Central Pacific of six large, five light, and six escort carriers prior to commencing these operations.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] From this point on, US cruisers primarily served as anti-aircraft escorts for carriers and in shore bombardment.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The only major Japanese carrier operation after Guadalcanal was the disastrous (for Japan) Battle of the Philippine Sea in June 1944, nicknamed the "Marianas Turkey Shoot" by the US Navy.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Imperial Japanese Navy's last major operation was the Battle of Leyte Gulf, an attempt to dislodge the American invasion of the Philippines in October 1944.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The two actions at this battle in which cruisers played a significant role were the Battle off Samar and the Battle of Surigao Strait.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Battle of Surigao Strait was fought on the night of 24–25 October, a few hours before the Battle off Samar.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese had a small battleship group composed of *Fusō* and *Yamashiro*, one heavy cruiser, and four destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] They were followed at a considerable distance by another small force of two heavy cruisers, a small light cruiser, and four destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Their goal was to head north through Surigao Strait and attack the invasion fleet off Leyte.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Allied force, known as the 7th Fleet Support Force, guarding the strait was overwhelming.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] It included six battleships (all but one previously damaged in 1941 at Pearl Harbor), four heavy cruisers (one Australian), four light cruisers, and 28 destroyers, plus a force of 39 PT boats.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The only advantage to the Japanese was that most of the Allied battleships and cruisers were loaded mainly with high explosive shells, although a significant number of armor-piercing shells were also loaded.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The lead Japanese force evaded the PT boats' torpedoes, but were hit hard by the destroyers' torpedoes, losing a battleship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Then they encountered the battleship and cruiser guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The engagement is notable for being one of only two occasions in which battleships fired on battleships in the Pacific Theater, the other being the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Due to the starting arrangement of the opposing forces, the Allied force was in a "crossing the T" position, so this was the last battle in which this occurred, but it was not a planned maneuver.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The following Japanese cruiser force had several problems, including a light cruiser damaged by a PT boat and two heavy cruisers colliding, one of which fell behind and was sunk by air attack the next day.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] An American veteran of Surigao Strait, USS *Phoenix*, was transferred to Argentina in 1951 as *General Belgrano*, becoming most famous for being sunk by HMS *Conqueror* in the Falklands War on 2 May 1982.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] She was the first ship sunk by a nuclear submarine outside of accidents, and only the second ship sunk by a submarine since World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] At the Battle off Samar, a Japanese battleship group moving towards the invasion fleet off Leyte engaged a minuscule American force known as "Taffy 3" (formally Task Unit 77.4.3), composed of six escort carriers with about 28 aircraft each, three destroyers, and four destroyer escorts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The biggest guns in the American force were 5 in (127 mm)/38 caliber guns, while the Japanese had 14 in (356 mm), 16 in (406 mm), and 18.1 in (460 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Aircraft from six additional escort carriers also participated for a total of around 330 US aircraft, a mix of F6F Hellcat fighters and TBF Avenger torpedo bombers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese had four battleships including *Yamato*, six heavy cruisers, two small light cruisers, and 11 destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese force had earlier been driven off by air attack, losing *Yamato*'s sister *Musashi*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Admiral Halsey then decided to use his Third Fleet carrier force to attack the Japanese carrier group, located well to the north of Samar, which was actually a decoy group with few aircraft.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Japanese were desperately short of aircraft and pilots at this point in the war, and Leyte Gulf was the first battle in which *kamikaze* attacks were used.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Due to a tragedy of errors, Halsey took the American battleship force with him, leaving San Bernardino Strait guarded only by the small Seventh Fleet escort carrier force.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The battle commenced at dawn on 25 October 1944, shortly after the Battle of Surigao Strait.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] In the engagement that followed, the Americans exhibited uncanny torpedo accuracy, blowing the bows off several Japanese heavy cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The escort carriers' aircraft also performed very well, attacking with machine guns after their carriers ran out of bombs and torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The unexpected level of damage, and maneuvering to avoid the torpedoes and air attacks, disorganized the Japanese and caused them to think they faced at least part of the Third Fleet's main force.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] They had also learned of the defeat a few hours before at Surigao Strait, and did not hear that Halsey's force was busy destroying the decoy fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Convinced that the rest of the Third Fleet would arrive soon if it hadn't already, the Japanese withdrew, eventually losing three heavy cruisers sunk with three damaged to air and torpedo attacks.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The Americans lost two escort carriers, two destroyers, and one destroyer escort sunk, with three escort carriers, one destroyer, and two destroyer escorts damaged, thus losing over one-third of their engaged force sunk with nearly all the remainder damaged.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The US built cruisers in quantity through the end of the war, notably 14 *Baltimore*-class heavy cruisers and 27 *Cleveland*-class light cruisers, along with eight *Atlanta*-class anti-aircraft cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The *Cleveland* class was the largest cruiser class ever built in number of ships completed, with nine additional *Cleveland*s completed as light aircraft carriers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] The large number of cruisers built was probably due to the significant cruiser losses of 1942 in the Pacific theater (seven American and five other Allied) and the perceived need for several cruisers to escort each of the numerous *Essex*-class aircraft carriers being built.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Losing four heavy and two small light cruisers in 1942, the Japanese built only five light cruisers during the war; these were small ships with six 6.1 in (155 mm) guns each.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p02] Losing 20 cruisers in 1940–42, the British completed no heavy cruisers, thirteen light cruisers (*Fiji* and *Minotaur* classes), and sixteen anti-aircraft cruisers (*Dido* class) during the war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The rise of air power during World War II dramatically changed the nature of naval combat.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Even the fastest cruisers could not maneuver quickly enough to evade aerial attack, and aircraft now had torpedoes, allowing moderate-range standoff capabilities.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The US Navy became centered around carrier groups, with cruisers and battleships primarily providing anti-aircraft defense and shore bombardment.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Until the Harpoon missile entered service in the late 1970s, the US Navy was almost entirely dependent on carrier-based aircraft and submarines for conventionally attacking enemy warships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Lacking aircraft carriers, the Soviet Navy depended on anti-ship cruise missiles; in the 1950s these were primarily delivered from heavy land-based bombers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Soviet submarine-launched cruise missiles at the time were primarily for land attack; but by 1964 anti-ship missiles were deployed in quantity on cruisers, destroyers, and submarines.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The US Navy was aware of the potential missile threat as soon as World War II ended, and had considerable related experience due to Japanese *kamikaze* attacks in that war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The initial response was to upgrade the light AA armament of new cruisers from 40 mm and 20 mm weapons to twin 3-inch (76 mm)/50 caliber gun mounts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] For the longer term, it was thought that gun systems would be inadequate to deal with the missile threat, and by the mid-1950s three naval SAM systems were developed: Talos (long range), Terrier (medium range), and Tartar (short range).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Talos and Terrier were nuclear-capable and this allowed their use in anti-ship or shore bombardment roles in the event of nuclear war.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Chief of Naval Operations Admiral Arleigh Burke is credited with speeding the development of these systems.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Terrier was initially deployed on two converted *Baltimore*-class cruisers (CAG), with conversions completed in 1955–56.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Further conversions of six *Cleveland*-class cruisers (CLG) (*Galveston* and *Providence* classes), redesign of the *Farragut* class as guided-missile "frigates" (DLG), and development of the *Charles F.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Adams*-class DDGs resulted in the completion of numerous additional guided-missile ships deploying all three systems in 1959–1962.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Also completed during this period was the nuclear-powered USS *Long Beach*, with two Terrier and one Talos launchers, plus an ASROC anti-submarine launcher the World War II conversions lacked.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The converted World War II cruisers up to this point retained one or two main battery turrets for shore bombardment.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] However, in 1962–1964 three additional *Baltimore* and *Oregon City*-class cruisers were more extensively converted as the *Albany* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These had two Talos and two Tartar launchers plus ASROC and two 5-inch (127 mm) guns for self-defense, and were primarily built to get greater numbers of Talos launchers deployed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Of all these types, only the *Farragut* DLGs were selected as the design basis for further production, although their *Leahy*-class successors were significantly larger (5,670 tons standard versus 4,150 tons standard) due to a second Terrier launcher and greater endurance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] An economical crew size compared with World War II conversions was probably a factor, as the *Leahy*s required a crew of only 377 versus 1,200 for the *Cleveland*-class conversions.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Through 1980, the ten *Farragut*s were joined by four additional classes and two one-off ships for a total of 36 guided-missile frigates, eight of them nuclear-powered (DLGN).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In 1975 the *Farragut*s were reclassified as guided-missile destroyers (DDG) due to their small size, and the remaining DLG/DLGN ships became guided-missile cruisers (CG/CGN).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The World War II conversions were gradually retired between 1970 and 1980; the Talos missile was withdrawn in 1980 as a cost-saving measure and the *Albany*s were decommissioned.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] *Long Beach* had her Talos launcher removed in a refit shortly thereafter; the deck space was used for Harpoon missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Around this time the Terrier ships were upgraded with the RIM-67 Standard ER missile.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The guided-missile frigates and cruisers served in the Cold War and the Vietnam War; off Vietnam they performed shore bombardment and shot down enemy aircraft or, as Positive Identification Radar Advisory Zone (PIRAZ) ships, guided fighters to intercept enemy aircraft.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] By 1995 the former guided-missile frigates were replaced by the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers and *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Navy's guided-missile cruisers were built upon destroyer-style hulls (some called "destroyer leaders" or "frigates" prior to the 1975 reclassification).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Navy's strike role was centered around aircraft carriers, cruisers were primarily designed to provide air defense while often adding anti-submarine capabilities.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These U.S. cruisers that were built in the 1960s and 1970s were larger, often nuclear-powered for extended endurance in escorting nuclear-powered fleet carriers, and carried longer-range surface-to-air missiles (SAMs) than early *Charles F.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Adams* guided-missile destroyers that were tasked with the short-range air defense role.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The U.S. cruiser was a major contrast to their contemporaries, Soviet "rocket cruisers" that were armed with large numbers of anti-ship cruise missiles (ASCMs) as part of the combat doctrine of saturation attack, though in the early 1980s the U.S.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Navy retrofitted some of these existing cruisers to carry a small number of Harpoon anti-ship missiles and Tomahawk cruise missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Navy cruisers and destroyers blurred with the *Spruance* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Like the *Ticonderoga* ships with VLS, the *Arleigh Burke* and *Zumwalt* class, despite being classified as destroyers, actually have much heavier anti-surface armament than previous U.S. ships classified as cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Following the American example, three smaller light cruisers of other NATO countries were rearmed with anti-aircraft missiles installed in place of their aft armament: the Dutch *De Zeven Provinciën*, the Italian *Giuseppe Garibaldi*, and the French *Colbert*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Only the French ship, rebuilt last in 1972, also received Exocet anti-ship missile launchers and domestically produced Masurca anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The others received American Terrier missiles, with *Garibaldi* uniquely among surface ships also being armed with Polaris strategic missile launchers, although these were never actually carried.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the Soviet Navy, only one cruiser, *Dzerzhinsky*, of Project 68bis, was similarly rearmed with anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The M-2 missiles used on it, adapted from the land-based S-75, proved ineffective as a naval system, and further conversions were abandoned.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Another cruiser of this project, *Admiral Nakhimov*, was used for testing anti-ship missiles but never entered service in this role.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The British considered converting older cruisers to guided-missile cruisers with the Seaslug system but ultimately did not proceed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The Peruvian light cruiser *Almirante Grau* (formerly the Dutch *De Ruyter*) was rearmed with eight Otomat anti-ship missiles at the end of the 20th century, but these did not constitute its primary armament.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Prior to the introduction of the *Ticonderoga*s, the US Navy used odd naming conventions that left its fleet seemingly without many cruisers, although a number of their ships were cruisers in all but name.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] From the 1950s to the 1970s, US Navy cruisers were large vessels equipped with heavy, specialized missiles (mostly surface-to-air, but for several years including the Regulus nuclear cruise missile) for wide-ranging combat against land-based and sea-based targets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Naming conventions changed, and some guided-missile cruisers were classified as frigates or destroyers during certain periods or at the construction stage.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] All save one—USS *Long Beach*—were converted from World War II cruisers of the *Oregon City*, *Baltimore* and *Cleveland* classes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Literature sometimes considers ships as cruisers even if they are not officially classified as such, primarily larger representatives of the Soviet large anti-submarine ship class, which had no equivalent in global classification.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Ultimately, after the 1975 classification reform in the US, larger ships were called cruisers, slightly smaller and weaker fleet escorts were called destroyers, and smaller ships for ocean escort and anti-submarine warfare were called frigates.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] However, the size and qualitative differences between them and destroyers were vague and arbitrary.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Frigates under this scheme were almost as large as the cruisers and optimized for anti-aircraft warfare, although they were capable anti-surface warfare combatants as well.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the late 1960s, the US government perceived a "cruiser gap"—at the time, the US Navy possessed six ships designated as cruisers, compared to 19 for the Soviet Union, even though the USN had 21 ships designated as frigates with equal or superior capabilities to the Soviet cruisers at the time.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Also, a series of Patrol Frigates of the *Oliver Hazard Perry* class, originally designated PFG, were redesignated into the FFG line.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The cruiser-destroyer-frigate realignment and the deletion of the Ocean Escort type brought the US Navy's ship designations into line with the rest of the world's, eliminating confusion with foreign navies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In 1980, the Navy's then-building DDG-47-class destroyers were redesignated as cruisers (*Ticonderoga* guided-missile cruisers) to emphasize the additional capability provided by the ships' Aegis combat systems, and their flag facilities suitable for an admiral and his staff.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the Soviet Navy, cruisers formed the basis of combat groups.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the immediate post-war era it built a fleet of gun-armed light cruisers, but replaced these beginning in the early 1960s with large ships called "rocket cruisers", carrying large numbers of anti-ship cruise missiles (ASCMs) and anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In 1962–1965 the four Kynda-class cruisers entered service; these had launchers for eight long-range SS-N-3 Shaddock ASCMs with a full set of reloads; these had a range of up to 450 kilometres (280 mi) with mid-course guidance.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The four more modest Kresta I-class cruisers, with launchers for four SS-N-3 ASCMs and no reloads, entered service in 1967–69.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In 1969–79 Soviet cruiser numbers more than tripled with ten Kresta II-class cruisers and seven Kara-class cruisers entering service.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These had launchers for eight large-diameter missiles whose purpose was initially unclear to NATO.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] This was the SS-N-14 Silex, an over/under rocket-delivered heavyweight torpedo primarily for the anti-submarine role, but capable of anti-surface action with a range of up to 90 kilometres (56 mi).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] By this time Long Range Aviation and the Soviet submarine force could deploy numerous ASCMs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Doctrine later shifted back to overwhelming carrier group defenses with ASCMs, with the *Slava* and *Kirov* classes.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] After the dissolution of the Soviet Union, the Russian cruiser *Moskva* of Project 1164 became the flagship of the Black Sea Fleet and in 2022 participated in the invasion of Ukraine, shelling and blockading the coast, but was subsequently sunk by anti-ship missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The end of the Cold War and the subsequent reduction of military rivalry led to significant reductions in naval forces.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] This reduction was more pronounced in the Soviet Navy, which was mostly taken over by Russia.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Faced with severe financial difficulties, Russia was forced to decommission most of its ships in the 1990s or send them for extended overhauls.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The most recent Soviet/Russian rocket cruisers, the four *Kirov*-class battlecruisers, were built in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] One of the *Kirov* class is in refit, and 2 are being scrapped, with the *Pyotr Velikiy* in active service.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Russia also operates two *Slava*-class cruisers and one *Admiral Kuznetsov*-class carrier which is officially designated as a cruiser, specifically a "heavy aviation cruiser" (Russian: тяжелый авианесущий крейсер) due to her complement of 12 P-700 Granit supersonic AShMs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In 2022, the cruiser *Moskva* of Project 1164 sank after being hit by a Ukrainian missile.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Currently, the *Kirov*-class heavy missile cruisers are used for command purposes, as *Pyotr Velikiy* is the flagship of the Northern Fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] However, their air defense capabilities are still powerful, as shown by the array of point defense missiles they carry, from 44 OSA-MA missiles to 196 9K311 Tor missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] For longer range targets, the S-300 is used.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] For closer range targets, AK-630 or Kashtan CIWSs are used.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Aside from that, *Kirov*s have 20 P-700 Granit missiles for anti-ship warfare.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] For target acquisition beyond the radar horizon, three helicopters can be used.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Besides a vast array of armament, *Kirov*-class cruisers are also outfitted with many sensors and communications equipment, allowing them to lead the fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The United States Navy has centered on the aircraft carrier since World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers, built in the 1980s, were originally designed and designated as a class of destroyer, intended to provide a very powerful air-defense in these carrier-centered fleets.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] As of 2020, the US Navy still had 22 of its newest *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers in service.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These ships were continuously upgraded, enhancing their value and versatility.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Some were equipped with ballistic missile defense capabilities (Aegis BMD system).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] However, no new cruisers of this class were being built.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the 21st century, there were design efforts for futuristic large cruisers provisionally designated as CG(X), but the program was canceled in 2010 due to budget constraints.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Formally, only the aforementioned ships are classified as cruisers globally.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The latest American futuristic large destroyers of the *Zumwalt* class, despite their displacement of approximately 16,000 tons and armament with two large-caliber (155 mm) guns traditionally associated with cruisers, are classified as destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Literature often emphasizes that these ships are essentially large cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Similarly, Japanese large missile destroyers of the *Kongō* class, with a displacement of 9,485 tons and equipped with the Aegis system (derived from the *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers), are sometimes referred to as cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Their improved versions, the *Atago* and *Maya* classes, exceed 10,000 tons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Japan, for political reasons, does not use the term "cruiser" or even "destroyer", formally classifying these ships as missile escorts with hull numbers prefixed by DDG, corresponding to guided-missile destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These Japanese destroyers also provide ballistic missile defense.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Outside the US and Soviet navies, new cruisers were rare following World War II.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Most navies use guided-missile destroyers for fleet air defense, and destroyers and frigates for cruise missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The need to operate in task forces has led most navies to change to fleets designed around ships dedicated to a single role, anti-submarine or anti-aircraft typically, and the large "generalist" ship has disappeared from most forces.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The United States Navy and the Russian Navy are the only remaining navies which operate active duty ships formally classed as cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Italy used *Vittorio Veneto* until 2003 (decommissioned in 2006) and the aircraft cruiser *Giuseppe Garibaldi* until 2024; France operated a single helicopter cruiser until May 2010, *Jeanne d'Arc*, for training purposes only.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] While Type 055 of the Chinese Navy is classified as a cruiser by the U.S.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Department of Defense, the Chinese consider it a guided-missile destroyer.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the years since the launch of *Ticonderoga* in 1981, the class has received a number of upgrades that have dramatically improved its members' capabilities for anti-submarine and land attack (using the Tomahawk missile).
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Like their Soviet counterparts, the modern *Ticonderoga*s can also be used as the basis for an entire battle group.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] From time to time, some navies have experimented with aircraft-carrying cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Another was the Japanese *Mogami*, which was converted to carry a large floatplane group in 1942.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Another variant is the *helicopter cruiser*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The further development of helicopter cruisers led to the creation of ships formally classified only as cruisers but significantly larger and effectively light aircraft carriers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the Soviet Union, a series of unusual hybrid ships of Project 1143 (*Kiev* class) were built in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Initially classified as anti-submarine cruisers, they were ultimately designated as "heavy aircraft cruisers".
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These ships combined the architecture of cruisers and aircraft carriers and were armed with long-range anti-ship and anti-aircraft missiles along with a deck for vertical take-off and landing aircraft.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Their full displacement of approximately 43,000 tons is typical for aircraft carriers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] By hosting several helicopters, their primary mission was also anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The last example in service was the Soviet Navy's *Kiev* class, whose last unit *Admiral Gorshkov* was converted to a pure aircraft carrier and sold to India as INS *Vikramaditya*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The Russian Navy's *Admiral Kuznetsov* is nominally designated as an aviation cruiser but otherwise resembles a standard medium aircraft carrier, albeit with a surface-to-surface missile battery.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] It was armed with missiles, but these were short-range self-defense missiles (anti-aircraft Aspide and anti-ship Otomat) and did not match the significance of its aviation capabilities.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Similarly, the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force's *Hyūga*-class "helicopter destroyers" are really more along the lines of helicopter cruisers in function and aircraft complement, but due to the Treaty of San Francisco, must be designated as destroyers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] One cruiser alternative studied in the late 1980s by the United States was variously entitled a Mission Essential Unit (MEU) or CG V/STOL.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In a return to the thoughts of the independent operations cruiser-carriers of the 1930s and the Soviet *Kiev* class, the ship was to be fitted with a hangar, elevators, and a flight deck.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The mission systems were Aegis, SQS-53 sonar, 12 SV-22 ASW aircraft and 200 VLS cells.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The resulting ship would have had a waterline length of 700 feet, a waterline beam of 97 feet, and a displacement of about 25,000 tons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Other features included an integrated electric drive and advanced computer systems, both stand-alone and networked.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The project was curtailed by the sudden end of the Cold War and its aftermath, otherwise the first of class would have been likely ordered in the early 1990s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] An alternative development path for guided-missile cruisers was represented by ships armed with heavy long-range anti-ship missiles, primarily developed in the Soviet Union with a focus on combating aircraft carriers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Starting in 1962, four ships of Project 58 (NATO designation: *Kynda*) entered service.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] They were armed with eight P-35 missile launchers with a range of 250 km and a twin launcher for M-1 Volna anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] With a moderate full displacement of 5,350 tons, they were initially intended to be classified as destroyers but ultimately entered service as guided-missile cruisers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] During this period, designs for larger cruisers, such as Project 64 and the nuclear-powered Project 63 (with 24 anti-ship missiles), were also developed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] However, their construction was abandoned due to high costs and vulnerability to air attacks due to the shortcomings of available anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The next built type was four ships of Project 1134 (NATO designation: *Kresta I*) with a displacement of 7,500 tons, equipped with four P-35 anti-ship missile launchers and two Volna anti-aircraft missile launchers.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These were transitional types with lesser strike capabilities and were initially classified as large anti-submarine ships but were reclassified as guided-missile cruisers in 1977.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In the 1980s, before the dissolution of the Soviet Union, only three guided-missile cruisers of the new generation Project 1164 (*Slava* class) with a full displacement of 11,300 tons were completed out of a longer planned series.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] They carried 16 Bazalt anti-ship missile launchers and eight vertical launchers for long-range Fort anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The pinnacle of development for cruisers designed to engage surface ships, while also protecting fleet formations from aircraft and submarines, was the four large nuclear-powered cruisers of Project 1144 (*Kirov* class) from the 1980s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] These were officially classified as "heavy nuclear guided-missile cruisers".
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] With a full displacement of up to 25,000 tons, they were armed with 20 Granit heavy anti-ship missile launchers, 12 vertical launchers for long-range Fort anti-aircraft missiles, and short-range missiles.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] For anti-submarine warfare, they were equipped with rocket-torpedo launchers and three helicopters, and their crew numbered up to 744 people.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] In English-language literature, they are sometimes referred to as "battlecruisers", although this designation lacks official justification.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The ship *Muntenia*, with a displacement of 5,790 tons, was constructed and built in Romania in the 1980s.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] It was initially somewhat ambitiously designated as a light helicopter cruiser but was reclassified as a destroyer in 1990, along with a name change.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] The ship and its classification reflected the ambitions of dictator Nicolae Ceaușescu amid limited industrial capabilities.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] It carried eight Soviet P-20M medium-range anti-ship missiles but lacked anti-aircraft missile armament and was equipped with two light helicopters without means for long-range anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] Few cruisers are still operational in the world's navies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/cruiser-p03] As of 2019, several decommissioned cruisers have been saved from scrapping and exist worldwide as museum ships.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The **French cruiser *Gloire*** was one of five *Gloire*-class armored cruisers built for the French Navy (*Marine Nationale*) in the first decade of the 20th century.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Fitted with a mixed armament of 194-millimeter (7.6 in) and 164.7-millimeter (6.5 in) guns, the ships were designed for service with the fleet.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Completed in 1904, *Gloire* joined her sister ships in the Northern Squadron (*Escadre du Nord*), usually serving as a flagship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] She participated in the French bombardment of Casablanca, Morocco, in 1907, and was briefly assigned to the Mediterranean Squadron (*Escadre de la Méditeranée*) in 1910–1911.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Gloire* became a training ship in late 1913.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] When World War I began in August 1914, she was assigned to patrol the English Channel to enforce the blockade of Germany and remained on that duty into 1916.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The cruiser was briefly deployed to French West Africa to search for German commerce raiders later that year before she was transferred to the French West Indies for several months.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Increased commerce raiding activity in early 1917 prompted a permanent deployment to the West Indies to escort convoys as part of the Atlantic Division (*Division de l'Atlantique*).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Gloire* remained there for at least a year after the war ended in November 1918 before she returned home to be placed in reserve.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The ship was stricken in 1922 and sold for scrap the following year.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The *Gloire*-class ships were designed by Emile Bertin as enlarged and improved versions of the preceding *Gueydon* class.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The ships measured 139.78 meters (458 ft 7 in) overall, with a beam of 20.2 meters (66 ft 3 in) and a draft of 7.55 meters (24 ft 9 in).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] They displaced 9,996 metric tons (9,838 long tons).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Their crew numbered 25 officers and 590 enlisted men.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The sisters' propulsion machinery consisted of three vertical triple-expansion steam engines, each driving a single propeller shaft, using steam provided by water-tube boilers, but the types of machinery differed between them.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Gloire* had three-cylinder engines fed by 28 Niclausse boilers that were designed to produce a total of 20,500 metric horsepower (15,100 kW) intended to give her a maximum speed of 21 knots (39 km/h; 24 mph).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The cruisers carried enough coal to give them a range of 6,500 nautical miles (12,000 km; 7,500 mi) at a speed of 10 knots (19 km/h; 12 mph).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The main battery of the *Gloire* class consisted of two quick-firing (QF) 194 mm Modèle 1893–1896 guns mounted in single-gun turrets fore and aft of the superstructure.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Their secondary armament comprised eight QF 164.7 mm Modèle 1893–1896 guns and six QF Canon de 100 mm (3.9 in) Modèle de 1893 guns.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Half of the 164.7 mm guns were in two singe-gun wing turrets on each broadside and all of the remaining guns were on single mounts in casemates in the hull.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] For defense against torpedo boats, they carried eighteen 47-millimeter (1.9 in) and four 37-millimeter (1.5 in) Hotchkiss guns, all of which were in single mounts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The sisters were also armed with five 450-millimeter (17.7 in) torpedo tubes, of which two were submerged and three above water.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Two of these were on each broadside and the fifth tube was in the stern.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] All of the above-water tubes were on pivot mounts.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The ships varied in the number of naval mines that they could carry and *Gloire* was fitted with storage for 12.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The *Gloire* class were the first French armored cruisers to have their waterline armored belt made from Harvey face-hardened armor plates.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The belt ranged in thickness from 70 to 150 millimeters (2.8 to 5.9 in).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Because of manufacturing limitations, the thinner end plates were nickel steel.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Behind the belt was a cofferdam, backed by a longitudinal watertight bulkhead.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The upper armored deck met the top of the belt and had a total thickness of 34 millimeters (1.3 in) while the lower armored deck curved down to meet the bottom of the belt and had a uniform thickness of 45 millimeters (1.8 in).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The main-gun turrets were protected by 161 millimeters (6.3 in) of Harvey armor, but their barbettes used 174-millimeter (6.9 in) plates of ordinary steel.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The face and sides of the secondary turrets were 92 millimeters (3.6 in) thick and the plates protecting their barbettes were 102 millimeters (4 in) thick.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The casemates protecting the 100-millimeter guns also had a thickness of 102 millimeters.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The face and sides of the conning tower were 174 millimeters thick.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] After a reorganization that saw the Mediterranean Squadron redesignated as the 1st Squadron (*1re Escadre*), *Gloire* and her sisters *Condé* and *Marseillaise* were assigned to the 2nd Light Division (*2e Division légère* (DL)) of the 1st Squadron by June 1910.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] As more modern armored cruisers entered service, they were concentrated in the Mediterranean and *Gloire* (now the divisional flagship), *Amiral Aube* and *Condé* were reunited by January 1911 in the Cruiser Division of the 2nd Squadron, as the Northern Squadron had been redesignated.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] In March the sisters visited New York City.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] When the *Danton*-class battleships began entering service in August, the French Navy reorganized yet again with the 2nd Squadron renumbered as the 3rd and the Cruiser Division was renamed as the 3rd DL by 4 September.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Gloire* was now the flagship of Rear Admiral Charles-Eugène Favereau.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The ship participated in the fleet review by the President of France, Armand Fallières, off Toulon that day.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] While conducting gunnery training on 20 September, a propellant charge exploded prematurely in one of her 194 mm gun turrets that killed nine and badly wounded another five crewmen.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] A memorial for the dead was conducted aboard the cruiser five days later.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] After the Agadir Crisis of 1911, the French and British governments agreed in 1912 that the Royal Navy would defend the northern French coast and the French would concentrate their fleet in the Mediterranean and defend British interests there.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The French forces left in the north were consolidated into the 2nd Light Squadron with the 3rd DL redesignated as the 1st Cruiser Squadron.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The ship was reassigned to the Atlantic Training Division (*Division d'instruction de l'Atlantique*) by 10 November 1913 where she served as the flagship of Rear Admiral Auguste-Georges Bouxin.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] As tensions rose during the July Crisis of 1914, *Gloire* and the other training cruisers were reactivated and assigned to the 2nd Light Division of the 2nd Light Squadron (*Escadre 2e légère*) which was tasked to defend the English Channel in conjunction with the British.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The 2nd DL was on station in the western end of the Channel by 4 August, where they were tasked to intercept German shipping and provide distant cover to the smaller ships escorting the transports conveying the British Expeditionary Force to France.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] On 27 October the French patrols in the Channel were reorganized with Rear Admiral François le Canellier aboard *Gloire* in control of the smaller cruisers now conducting the patrols.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The successes of German merchant raiders like *Möwe* in 1916 caused the Allies to transfer cruisers to the Atlantic to protect their shipping.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Gloire*, was temporarily assigned to the 3rd DL when she was sent to Dakar, French West Africa, in February, but returned two months later.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] After another reorganization in May, *Gloire* and all of her sisters were assigned to the 3rd DL which was tasked with patrolling the West Indies in search of German commerce raiders.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Together with *Amiral Aube*, *Gloire* departed Brest on 20 May, bound for Fort-de-France in the colony of Martinique to rendezvous with *Marseillaise* and *Condé* which were already there.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The armored cruisers were relieved by the 4th DL in September.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Möwe* and two other raiders began cruises in late 1916.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Gloire* left Brest in an unsuccessful attempt to intercept *Möwe* in late December off Halifax and returned on 17 January 1917.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Not long afterwards she returned to the West Indies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The 3rd DL was disbanded on 18 May and the remaining cruisers in the West Indies were assigned to the 4th DL which was redesignated as the Atlantic and Antilles Division (*Division de l'Atlantique et des Antilles*) on 1 June with *Gloire* as its flagship.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The division was tasked with escorting convoys bound for Europe from Saint Thomas, U.S.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] Virgin Islands beginning on 15 February 1918.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] In May the cruiser collided with the American ocean liner SS *City of Athens* and was sent back to France for repairs.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] *Gloire* returned to the West Indies and became flagship again when the division was renamed the Atlantic Division on 25 June.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The convoy escort responsibilities were reorganized on 7 July with the French covering convoys from New York City to the Bay of Biscay.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] She was still assigned to the division when the war ended on 11 November and she escorted the ocean liner SS *Leviathan* bringing General John Pershing back to the United States on 1 September 1919.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1900] The ship was subsequently placed in reserve before she was stricken from the naval register on 7 July 1922 and was sold for scrap in 1923.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] The *La Galissonnière* class was designed as an enlarged and improved version of the preceding *Emile Bertin*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] The ships had an overall length of 179.5 meters (588 ft 11 in), a beam of 17.48 meters (57 ft 4 in), and a draft of 5.28 meters (17 ft 4 in).
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] They displaced 7,722 metric tons (7,600 long tons) at standard load and 9,460 t (9,310 long tons) at deep load.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] Their crew consisted of 557 men in peacetime and 612 in wartime.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] After completing trials, *Gloire* arrived in Brest on 18 November 1937, then left for French Indochina on 1 December, returning to Brest on 16 April 1938.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] *Gloire* joined the 4th Cruiser Division in January 1939, with which she visited Britain and the United States.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] She was refitted between October and December 1939.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] She then sailed for Canada with the battleship *Dunkerque*, carrying gold, and subsequently escorted a Canadian troop convoy on her return.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] Atlantic patrols as part of Vice Admiral Marcel-Bruno Gensoul's *Force de Raid* followed.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] At the time of the French surrender in June 1940, *Gloire* was at Algiers, but returned to Toulon on 4 July, where the 4th Cruiser Division formed part of the French Independent Naval Force.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] Between April and July, *Gloire* underwent a refit at Casablanca, and on 12 September 1942 took part in the rescue operations after the passenger liner *Laconia* had been sunk, arriving on the scene in the evening of 17 September.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] After the Allied invasion of north Africa (Operation Torch) and the consequent abrogation by the Germans of the armistice (Case Anton) in November 1942, *Gloire* rejoined the Allies.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] Three surviving *La Galissonnière*-class cruisers, based at Dakar, were refitted in 1943.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] Unlike her sisters which were refitted at Philadelphia, instead she was refitted at New York. removing aircraft installations and adding light anti-aircraft weapons.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] *Gloire* then operated from Dakar together with other French and Italian cruisers, searching for Axis blockade runners in the central and south Atlantic until 16 January 1944, when she moved to the Mediterranean.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] In February, she supported the Allied landings at Anzio, bombarding enemy positions in the Bay of Gaeta (firing 604 rounds) and transporting troops to Italy and Corsica.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] After a refit at Algiers between 27 April and 17 June, she participated in the landing in the south of France (Operation Dragoon) in August, firing nearly 2,000 rounds in shore support between 15 and 28 August.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] *Gloire* continued to support Allied forces along the French and Italian Rivieras until the end of the war, except for a special trip to the United States in December.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-cruiser-gloire-1935] Postwar, *Gloire* made three deployments to Indo-China and she was finally placed in reserve on 1 February 1955, being condemned for disposal on 2 January 1958.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-frigate-gloire-1803] She took part in Allemand's expedition of 1805.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-frigate-gloire-1803] On 18 July, she captured and burnt a Prussian cutter to maintain the secrecy of the movements of the fleet, in spite of the neutrality of Prussia at the time.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-frigate-gloire-1803] The next day, along with *Armide*, she captured HMS *Ranger* and burnt her.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-frigate-gloire-1803] In the action of 25 September 1806, *Armide*, *Gloire*, *Minerve* and *Infatigable* were captured by a four-ship squadron under Samuel Hood.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-frigate-gloire-1803] She was brought into British service as HMS ***Gloire*** and broken up in 1812.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-frigate-gloire-1837] On 18 August 1847, she ran aground on an island off the western coast of Korea, along with the frigate *Victorieuse*.
[src:french-ship-gloire/french-frigate-gloire-1837] Two boats made it to Shanghai to request assistance, and the marooned crew was picked up by HMS *Daedalus*, HMS *Espiegle*, and HMS *Childers* on 12 September 1847.
